# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: brittany
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] A major worldwide financial crisis centered in the United States took place in 2008.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The causes included excessive speculation on property values by both homeowners and financial institutions, leading to the 2000s United States housing bubble.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] This was exacerbated by predatory lending for subprime mortgages and by deficiencies in regulation.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Cash out refinancings had fueled an increase in consumption that could no longer be sustained when home prices declined.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The first phase of the crisis was the subprime mortgage crisis, which began in early 2007, as mortgage-backed securities (MBS) tied to U.S. real estate, and a vast web of derivatives linked to those MBS collapsed in value.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] A liquidity crisis spread to global institutions by mid-2007 and climaxed with the bankruptcy of Lehman Brothers in September 2008, which triggered a stock market crash and bank runs in several countries.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The crisis exacerbated the Great Recession, a global recession that began in late-2007, as well as the United States bear market of 2007–2009.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] It was also a contributor to the 2008–2011 Icelandic financial crisis and the euro area crisis.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] As the Federal Reserve ("Fed") lowered the federal funds rate from 2000 to 2003, institutions increasingly targeted low-income homebuyers, largely belonging to racial minorities, with high-risk loans; this development went unattended by regulators.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] As interest rates rose from 2004 to 2006, the cost of mortgages rose and the demand for housing fell; in early 2007, as more U.S. subprime mortgage holders began defaulting on their repayments, lenders went bankrupt, culminating in the bankruptcy of New Century Financial in April.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] As demand and prices continued to fall, the financial contagion spread to global credit markets by August 2007, and central banks began injecting liquidity.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In March 2008, Bear Stearns, the fifth-largest U.S. investment bank, was sold to JPMorgan Chase in a "fire sale" backed by Fed financing.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In response to the growing crisis, governments around the world deployed massive bailouts of financial institutions and used monetary policy and fiscal policies to prevent an economic collapse of the global financial system.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] By July 2008, Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, companies which together owned or guaranteed half of the U.S. housing market, verged on collapse; the Housing and Economic Recovery Act of 2008 enabled the federal government to seize them on September 7.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] On October 3, Congress passed the Emergency Economic Stabilization Act, authorizing the Treasury Department to purchase toxic assets and bank stocks through the $700 billion Troubled Asset Relief Program (TARP).
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Fed began a program of quantitative easing by buying treasury bonds and other assets, such as MBS, and the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act, signed in February 2009 by newly elected president Barack Obama, included a range of measures intended to preserve existing jobs and create new ones.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] These initiatives combined, coupled with actions taken in other countries, ended the worst of the Great Recession by mid-2009.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Assessments of the crisis's impact in the U.S. vary, but suggest that some 8.7 million jobs were lost, causing unemployment to rise from 5% in 2007 to a high of 10% in October 2009.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The percentage of citizens living in poverty rose from 12.5% in 2007 to 15.1% in 2010.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell by 53% between October 2007 and March 2009, and some estimates suggest that one in four households lost 75% or more of their net worth.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In 2010, the Dodd–Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act was passed, overhauling financial regulations.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] It was opposed by many Republicans, and it was weakened by the Economic Growth, Regulatory Relief, and Consumer Protection Act in 2018.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Basel III capital and liquidity standards were also adopted by countries around the world.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The crisis exacerbated the Great Recession, a global recession that began in mid-2007.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] It was among the five worst financial crises the world had experienced and led to a loss of more than $2 trillion from the global economy.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] U.S. home mortgage debt relative to GDP increased from an average of 46% during the 1990s to 73% during 2008, reaching $10.5 (~$15 trillion in 2024) trillion.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The increase in cash out refinancings, as home values rose, fueled an increase in consumption that could no longer be sustained when home prices declined.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Many financial institutions owned investments whose value was based on home mortgages such as mortgage-backed securities, or credit derivatives used to insure them against failure, which declined in value significantly.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The International Monetary Fund estimated that large U.S. and European banks lost more than $1 trillion on toxic assets and from bad loans from January 2007 to September 2009.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Lack of investor confidence in bank solvency and declines in credit availability led to plummeting stock and commodity prices in late 2008 and early 2009.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The crisis rapidly spread into a global economic shock, resulting in several bank failures.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Economies worldwide slowed during this period since credit tightened and international trade declined.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Housing markets suffered and unemployment soared, resulting in evictions and foreclosures.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] From its peak in the second quarter of 2007 at $61.4 trillion, household wealth in the United States fell $11 trillion, to $50.4 trillion by the end of the first quarter of 2009, resulting in a decline in consumption, then a decline in business investment.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In the fourth quarter of 2008, the quarter-over-quarter decline in real GDP in the U.S. was 8.4%.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The U.S. unemployment rate peaked at 11.0% in October 2009, the highest rate since 1983 and roughly twice the pre-crisis rate.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The average hours per work week declined to 33, the lowest level since the government began collecting the data in 1964.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The economic crisis started in the U.S. but spread to the rest of the world.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] U.S. consumption accounted for more than a third of the growth in global consumption between 2000 and 2007 and the rest of the world depended on the U.S. consumer as a source of demand.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Toxic securities were owned by corporate and institutional investors globally.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Derivatives such as credit default swaps also increased the linkage between large financial institutions.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The de-leveraging of financial institutions, as assets were sold to pay back obligations that could not be refinanced in frozen credit markets, further accelerated the solvency crisis and caused a decrease in international trade.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Reductions in the growth rates of developing countries were due to falls in trade, commodity prices, investment and remittances sent from migrant workers (example: Armenia).
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] States with fragile political systems feared that investors from Western states would withdraw their money because of the crisis.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In effect, the central banks went from being the "lender of last resort" to the "lender of only resort" for a significant portion of the economy.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In some cases the Fed was considered the "buyer of last resort".
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] During the fourth quarter of 2008, these central banks purchased US$2.5 trillion (~$3.57 trillion in 2024) of government debt and troubled private assets from banks.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] This was the largest liquidity injection into the credit market, and the largest monetary policy action in world history.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Federal Reserve created then-significant amounts of new currency as a method to combat the liquidity trap.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Bailouts came in the form of trillions of dollars of loans, asset purchases, guarantees, and direct spending.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Significant controversy accompanied the bailouts, such as in the case of the AIG bonus payments controversy, leading to the development of a variety of "decision making frameworks", to help balance competing policy interests during times of financial crisis.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Alistair Darling, the U.K.'s Chancellor of the Exchequer at the time of the crisis, stated in 2018 that Britain came within hours of "a breakdown of law and order" the day that Royal Bank of Scotland was bailed-out.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Instead of financing more domestic loans, some banks instead spent some of the stimulus money in more profitable areas such as investing in emerging markets and foreign currencies.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In July 2010, the Dodd–Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act was enacted in the United States to "promote the financial stability of the United States".
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Basel III capital and liquidity standards were adopted worldwide.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Since the 2008 financial crisis, consumer regulators in America have more closely supervised sellers of credit cards and home mortgages in order to deter anticompetitive practices that led to the crisis.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] At least two major reports on the causes of the crisis were produced by the U.S.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Congress: the Financial Crisis Inquiry Commission report, released January 2011, and a report by the United States Senate Homeland Security Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations entitled Wall Street and the Financial Crisis: Anatomy of a Financial Collapse, released April 2011.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In total, 47 bankers served jail time as a result of the crisis, over half of whom were from Iceland, where the crisis was the most severe and led to the collapse of all three major Icelandic banks.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In April 2012, Geir Haarde of Iceland became the only politician to be convicted as a result of the crisis.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In the aftermath of the crisis, U.S. authorities intensified enforcement actions against financial misconduct, including high-profile insider trading prosecutions such as that of Raj Rajaratnam, who was convicted in 2011.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Only one banker in the United States served jail time as a result of the crisis, Kareem Serageldin, a banker at Credit Suisse who was sentenced to 30 months in jail and returned $24.6 million in compensation for manipulating bond prices to hide $1 billion of losses.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] No individuals in the United Kingdom were convicted as a result of the crisis.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Goldman Sachs*, Goldman Sachs paid a $550 million civil penalty and acknowledged that its marketing materials for CDO contained incomplete information, settling securities fraud charges after allegedly anticipating the financial crisis and selling toxic investments to its clients.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] With fewer resources to risk in creative destruction, the number of patent applications was flat, compared to exponential increases in patent application in prior years.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Typical American families did not fare well, nor did the "wealthy-but-not-wealthiest" families just beneath the pyramid's top.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] However, half of the poorest families in the United States did not have wealth declines at all during the crisis because they generally did not own financial investments whose value could fluctuate.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Federal Reserve surveyed 4,000 households from 2007 to 2009, and found that the total wealth of 63% of all Americans declined in that period and 77% of the richest families had a decrease in total wealth, while only 50% of those on the bottom of the pyramid suffered a decrease.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The following is a timeline of the major events of the financial crisis, including government responses, and the subsequent economic recovery.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In the table, the names of emerging and developing economies are shown in boldface type, while the names of developed economies are in Roman (regular) type.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The expansion of central bank lending in response to the crisis was not confined to the Federal Reserve's provision of aid to individual financial institutions.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Federal Reserve has also conducted several innovative lending programs to improve liquidity and strengthen different financial institutions and markets, such as Freddie Mac and Fannie Mae.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In this case, the major problem in the market is the lack of free cash reserves and flows to secure the loans.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Federal Reserve took many steps to deal with financial market liquidity worries.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] One of these steps was a credit line for major traders, who act as the Fed's partners in open market activities.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Also, loan programs were set up to make the money market mutual funds and commercial paper market more flexible.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Also, the Term Asset-Backed Securities Loan Facility (TALF) was put in place thanks to a joint effort with the US Department of the Treasury.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] This plan made it easier for consumers and businesses to get credit by giving Americans who owned high-quality asset-backed securities more credit.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Before the crisis, the Federal Reserve's stocks of Treasury securities were sold to pay for the increase in credit.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] This method was meant to keep banks from trying to give out their extra savings, which could cause the federal funds rate to drop below where it was supposed to be.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] However, in October 2008, the Federal Reserve was granted the power to provide banks with interest payments on their surplus reserves.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] This created a motivation for banks to retain their reserves instead of disbursing them, thus reducing the need for the Federal Reserve to hedge its increased lending by decreases in alternative assets.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Money market funds also went through runs when people lost faith in the market.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] To keep it from getting worse, the Fed said it would give money to mutual fund companies.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Also, the Department of Treasury said that it would briefly cover the assets of the fund.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Both of these things helped get the fund market back to normal, which helped the commercial paper market, which most businesses use to run.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The FDIC also did several things, such as raising the insurance cap from $100,000 to $250,000, to boost customer trust.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] They engaged in quantitative easing, which added more than $4 trillion to the financial system and got banks to start lending again, both to each other and to people.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Many homeowners who were trying to keep their homes from going into default got housing credits.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p01] A package of policies was passed that let borrowers refinance their loans even though the value of their homes was less than what they still owed on their mortgages.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The relaxing of credit lending standards by investment banks and commercial banks allowed for a significant increase in subprime lending.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Subprime had not become less risky; Wall Street just accepted this higher risk.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Due to competition between mortgage lenders for revenue and market share, and when the supply of creditworthy borrowers was limited, mortgage lenders relaxed underwriting standards and originated riskier mortgages to less creditworthy borrowers.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In the view of some analysts, the relatively conservative government-sponsored enterprises (GSEs) policed mortgage originators and maintained relatively high underwriting standards prior to 2003.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] However, as market power shifted from securitizers to originators, and as intense competition from private securitizers undermined GSE power, mortgage standards declined and risky loans proliferated.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The riskiest loans were originated in 2004–2007, the years of the most intense competition between securitizers and the lowest market share for the GSEs.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The GSEs eventually relaxed their standards to try to catch up with the private banks.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Depending on how "subprime" mortgages are defined, they remained below 10% of all mortgage originations until 2004, when they rose to nearly 20% and remained there through the 2005–2006 peak of the United States housing bubble.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Although they concede that governmental policies had some role in causing the crisis, they contend that GSE loans performed better than loans securitized by private investment banks, and performed better than some loans originated by institutions that held loans in their own portfolios.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In his dissent to the majority report of the Financial Crisis Inquiry Commission, conservative American Enterprise Institute fellow Peter J.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Based upon information in the SEC's December 2011 securities fraud case against six former executives of Fannie and Freddie, Peter Wallison and Edward Pinto estimated that, in 2008, Fannie and Freddie held 13 million substandard loans totaling over $2 trillion.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In the early and mid-2000s, the Bush administration called numerous times for investigations into the safety and soundness of the GSEs and their swelling portfolio of subprime mortgages.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The hearings never resulted in new legislation or formal investigation of Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, as many of the committee members refused to accept the report and instead rebuked OFHEO for their attempt at regulation.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Some, such as Wallison, believe this was an early warning to the systemic risk that the growing market in subprime mortgages posed to the U.S. financial system that went unheeded.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Sub-prime loans made by CRA-covered institutions constituted a 3% market share of LMI loans in 1998, but in the run-up to the crisis, fully 25% of all subprime lending occurred at CRA-covered institutions and another 25% of subprime loans had some connection with CRA.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] To other analysts the delay between CRA rule changes in 1995 and the explosion of subprime lending is not surprising, and does not exonerate the CRA.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] They contend that there were two, connected causes to the crisis: the relaxation of underwriting standards in 1995 and the ultra-low interest rates initiated by the Federal Reserve after the terrorist attack on September 11, 2001.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Both causes had to be in place before the crisis could take place.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Critics also point out that publicly announced CRA loan commitments were massive, totaling $4.5 trillion in the years between 1994 and 2007.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] They also argue that the Federal Reserve's classification of CRA loans as "prime" is based on the faulty and self-serving assumption that high-interest-rate loans (3 percentage points over average) equal "subprime" loans.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Others have pointed out that there were not enough of these loans made to cause a crisis of this magnitude.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By March 2011, the FDIC had paid out $9 billion (c. $12.3 billion in 2024) to cover losses on bad loans at 165 failed financial institutions.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The Congressional Budget Office estimated, in June 2011, that the bailout to Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac exceeds $300 billion (c. $411 billion in 2024) (calculated by adding the fair value deficits of the entities to the direct bailout funds at the time).
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In other words, bubbles in both markets developed even though only the residential market was affected by these potential causes.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] *residential housing* bubble (as opposed to other types of bubbles) led to financial crisis was that it was supported by a huge number of substandard loans—generally with low or no downpayments.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Krugman's contention (that the growth of a commercial real estate bubble indicates that U.S. housing policy was not the cause of the crisis) is challenged by additional analysis.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] After researching the default of commercial loans during the financial crisis, Xudong An and Anthony B.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Business journalist Kimberly Amadeo reported: "The first signs of decline in residential real estate occurred in 2006.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Three years later, commercial real estate started feeling the effects." Denice A.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Between 1998 and 2006, the price of the typical American house increased by 124%.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] During the 1980s and 1990s, the national median home price ranged from 2.9 to 3.1 times median household income.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By contrast, this ratio increased to 4.0 in 2004, and 4.6 in 2006.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This housing bubble resulted in many homeowners refinancing their homes at lower interest rates, or financing consumer spending by taking out second mortgages secured by the price appreciation.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In a Peabody Award-winning program, NPR correspondents argued that a "Giant Pool of Money" (represented by $70 trillion in worldwide fixed income investments) sought higher yields than those offered by U.S.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This pool of money had roughly doubled in size from 2000 to 2007, yet the supply of relatively safe, income generating investments had not grown as fast.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Investment banks on Wall Street answered this demand with products such as the mortgage-backed security and the collateralized debt obligation that were assigned safe ratings by the credit rating agencies.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In effect, Wall Street connected this pool of money to the mortgage market in the US, with enormous fees accruing to those throughout the mortgage supply chain, from the mortgage broker selling the loans to small banks that funded the brokers and the large investment banks behind them.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By approximately 2003, the supply of mortgages originated at traditional lending standards had been exhausted, and continued strong demand began to drive down lending standards.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The collateralized debt obligation in particular enabled financial institutions to obtain investor funds to finance subprime and other lending, extending or increasing the housing bubble and generating large fees.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This essentially places cash payments from multiple mortgages or other debt obligations into a single pool from which specific securities draw in a specific sequence of priority.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Those securities first in line received investment-grade ratings from rating agencies.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Securities with lower priority had lower credit ratings but theoretically a higher rate of return on the amount invested.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By September 2008, average U.S. housing prices had declined by over 20% from their mid-2006 peak.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] As prices declined, borrowers with adjustable-rate mortgages could not refinance to avoid the higher payments associated with rising interest rates and began to default.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] During 2007, lenders began foreclosure proceedings on nearly 1.3 million properties, a 79% increase over 2006.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This increased to 2.3 million in 2008, an 81% increase vs.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By August 2008, approximately 9% of all U.S. mortgages outstanding were either delinquent or in foreclosure.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By September 2009, this had risen to 14.4%.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] After the bubble burst, Australian economist John Quiggin wrote: "And, unlike the Great Depression, this crisis was entirely the product of financial markets.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Lower interest rates encouraged borrowing.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] From 2000 to 2003, the Federal Reserve lowered the federal funds rate target from 6.5% to 1.0%.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This was done to soften the effects of the collapse of the dot-com bubble and the September 11 attacks, as well as to combat a perceived risk of deflation.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] As early as 2002, it was apparent that credit was fueling housing instead of business investment as some economists went so far as to advocate that the Fed "needs to create a housing bubble to replace the Nasdaq bubble".
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Moreover, empirical studies using data from advanced countries show that excessive credit growth contributed greatly to the severity of the crisis.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Additional downward pressure on interest rates was created by a growing U.S. current account deficit, which peaked along with the housing bubble in 2006.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Federal Reserve chairman Ben Bernanke explained how trade deficits required the U.S. to borrow money from abroad, in the process bidding up bond prices and lowering interest rates.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Bernanke explained that between 1996 and 2004, the U.S. current account deficit increased by $650 billion, from 1.5% to 5.8% of GDP.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Financing these deficits required the country to borrow large sums from abroad, much of it from countries running trade surpluses.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] These were mainly the emerging economies in Asia and oil-exporting nations.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The balance of payments identity requires that a country (such as the US) running a current account deficit also have a capital account (investment) surplus of the same amount.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Hence large and growing amounts of foreign funds (capital) flowed into the U.S. to finance its imports.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] All of this created demand for various types of financial assets, raising the prices of those assets while lowering interest rates.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Foreign investors had these funds to lend either because they had very high personal savings rates (as high as 40% in China) or because of high oil prices.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Ben Bernanke referred to this as a "saving glut".
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] A flood of funds (capital or liquidity) reached the U.S. financial markets.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Foreign governments supplied funds by purchasing Treasury bonds and thus avoided much of the direct effect of the crisis.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] U.S. households used funds borrowed from foreigners to finance consumption or to bid up the prices of housing and financial assets.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Financial institutions invested foreign funds in mortgage-backed securities.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The Fed then raised the Fed funds rate significantly between July 2004 and July 2006.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This contributed to an increase in one-year and five-year adjustable-rate mortgage (ARM) rates, making ARM interest rate resets more expensive for homeowners.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This may have also contributed to the deflation of the housing bubble, as asset prices generally move inversely to interest rates.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] It became riskier to speculate in housing.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] U.S. housing and financial assets dramatically declined in value after the housing bubble burst.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Subprime lending standards declined in the U.S.: in early 2000, a subprime borrower had a FICO score of 660 or less.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By 2005, many lenders dropped the required FICO score to 620, making it much easier to qualify for prime loans and making subprime lending a riskier business.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Proof of income and assets were de-emphasized.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Loans at first required full documentation, then low documentation, then no documentation.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] One subprime mortgage product that gained wide acceptance was the no income, no job, no asset verification required (NINJA) mortgage.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Informally, these loans were aptly referred to as "liar loans" because they encouraged borrowers to be less than honest in the loan application process.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Testimony given to the Financial Crisis Inquiry Commission by whistleblower Richard M.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Bowen III on events during his tenure as the Business Chief Underwriter for Correspondent Lending in the Consumer Lending Group for Citigroup, where he was responsible for over 220 professional underwriters, suggests that by 2006 and 2007, the collapse of mortgage underwriting standards was endemic.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] His testimony stated that by 2006, 60% of mortgages purchased by Citigroup from some 1,600 mortgage companies were "defective" (were not underwritten to policy, or did not contain all policy-required documents).
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This, despite the fact that each of these 1,600 originators was contractually responsible (certified via representations and warrantees) that its mortgage originations met Citigroup standards.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Moreover, during 2007, "defective mortgages (from mortgage originators contractually bound to perform underwriting to Citi's standards) increased to over 80% of production".
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The analysis, conducted on behalf of 23 investment and commercial banks, including 7 "too big to fail" banks, additionally showed that 28% of the sampled loans did not meet the minimal standards of any issuer.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Clayton's analysis further showed that 39% of these loans (i.e. those not meeting *any* issuer's minimal underwriting standards) were subsequently securitized and sold to investors.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Predatory lending refers to the practice of unscrupulous lenders enticing borrowers to enter into unfair or abusive secured loans for inappropriate purposes.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In May 2009, Bank of America modified 64,000 Countrywide loans as a result.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] When housing prices decreased, homeowners in ARMs then had little incentive to pay their monthly payments, since their home equity had disappeared.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This caused Countrywide's financial condition to deteriorate, ultimately resulting in a decision by the Office of Thrift Supervision to seize the lender.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Former employees from Ameriquest, which was the United States' leading wholesale lender, described a system in which they were pushed to falsify mortgage documents and then sell the mortgages to Wall Street banks eager to make fast profits.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] There is growing evidence that such mortgage frauds may be a cause of the crisis.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] According to Barry Eichengreen, the roots of the financial crisis lay in the deregulation of financial markets.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] A 2012 OECD study suggested that bank regulation based on the Basel accords encouraged unconventional business practices and contributed to or reinforced the financial crisis.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In other cases, laws were changed or enforcement weakened in parts of the financial system.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Prior to the crisis, financial institutions became highly leveraged, increasing their appetite for risky investments and reducing their resilience in case of losses.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Much of this leverage was achieved using complex financial instruments such as off-balance sheet securitization and derivatives, which made it difficult for creditors and regulators to monitor and try to reduce financial institution risk levels.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] U.S. households and financial institutions became increasingly indebted or overleveraged during the years preceding the crisis.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This increased their vulnerability to the collapse of the housing bubble and worsened the ensuing economic downturn.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Free cash used by consumers from home equity extraction doubled from $627 billion in 2001 to $1,428 billion in 2005 as the housing bubble built, a total of nearly $5 trillion over the period, contributing to economic growth worldwide.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p02] U.S. home mortgage debt relative to GDP increased from an average of 46% during the 1990s to 73% during 2008, reaching $10.5 trillion (c. $15 trillion in 2024).
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] U.S. household debt as a percentage of annual disposable personal income was 127% at the end of 2007, versus 77% in 1990.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In 1981, U.S. private debt was 123% of GDP; by the third quarter of 2008, it was 290%.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] From 2004 to 2007, the top five U.S. investment banks each significantly increased their financial leverage, which increased their vulnerability to a financial shock.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Changes in capital requirements, intended to keep U.S. banks competitive with their European counterparts, allowed lower *risk weightings* for AAA-rated securities.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The shift from first-loss tranches to AAA-rated tranches was seen by regulators as a risk reduction that compensated the higher leverage.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] These five institutions reported over $4.1 trillion in debt for fiscal year 2007, about 30% of U.S. nominal GDP for 2007.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Lehman Brothers went bankrupt and was liquidated, Bear Stearns and Merrill Lynch were sold at fire-sale prices, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley became commercial banks, subjecting themselves to more stringent regulation.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] With the exception of Lehman, these companies required or received government support.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, two U.S. government-sponsored enterprises, owned or guaranteed nearly $5 trillion (c. $7.13 trillion in 2024) trillion in mortgage obligations at the time they were placed into conservatorship by the U.S. government in September 2008.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] These seven entities were highly leveraged and had $9 trillion in debt or guarantee obligations; yet they were not subject to the same regulation as depository banks.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Behavior that may be optimal for an individual, such as saving more during adverse economic conditions, can be detrimental if too many individuals pursue the same behavior, as ultimately one person's consumption is another person's income.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Too many consumers attempting to save or pay down debt simultaneously is called the paradox of thrift and can cause or deepen a recession.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Economist Hyman Minsky also described a "paradox of deleveraging" as financial institutions that have too much leverage (debt relative to equity) cannot all de-leverage simultaneously without significant declines in the value of their assets.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The term financial innovation refers to the ongoing development of financial products designed to achieve particular client objectives, such as offsetting a particular risk exposure (such as the default of a borrower) or to assist with obtaining financing.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The usage of these products expanded dramatically in the years leading up to the crisis.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] These products vary in complexity and the ease with which they can be valued on the books of financial institutions.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] CDO issuance grew from an estimated $20 billion in Q1 2004 to its peak of over $180 billion by Q1 2007, then declined back under $20 billion by Q1 2008.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Further, the credit quality of CDO's declined from 2000 to 2007, as the level of subprime and other non-prime mortgage debt increased from 5% to 36% of CDO assets.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] As described in the section on subprime lending, the CDS and portfolio of CDS called synthetic CDO enabled a theoretically infinite amount to be wagered on the finite value of housing loans outstanding, provided that buyers and sellers of the derivatives could be found.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] For example, buying a CDS to insure a CDO ended up giving the seller the same risk as if they owned the CDO, when those CDO's became worthless.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This boom in innovative financial products went hand in hand with more complexity.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] It multiplied the number of actors connected to a single mortgage (including mortgage brokers, specialized originators, the securitizers and their due diligence firms, managing agents and trading desks, and finally investors, insurances and providers of repo funding).
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Instead of spreading risk this provided the ground for fraudulent acts, misjudgments and finally market collapse.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Economists have studied the crisis as an instance of cascades in financial networks, where institutions' instability destabilized other institutions and led to knock-on effects.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Mortgage risks were underestimated by almost all institutions in the chain from originator to investor by underweighting the possibility of falling housing prices based on historical trends of the past 50 years.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] While financial derivatives and structured products helped partition and shift risk between financial participants, it was the underestimation of falling housing prices and the resultant losses that led to aggregate risk.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] For a variety of reasons, market participants did not accurately measure the risk inherent with financial innovation such as MBS and CDOs or understand its effect on the overall stability of the financial system.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The pricing model for CDOs clearly did not reflect the level of risk they introduced into the system.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] AIG insured obligations of various financial institutions through the usage of credit default swaps.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The basic CDS transaction involved AIG receiving a premium in exchange for a promise to pay money to party A in the event party B defaulted.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] However, AIG did not have the financial strength to support its many CDS commitments as the crisis progressed and was taken over by the government in September 2008.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] U.S. taxpayers provided over $180 billion in government loans and investments in AIG during 2008 and early 2009, through which the money flowed to various counterparties to CDS transactions, including many large global financial institutions.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The Financial Crisis Inquiry Commission (FCIC) made the major government study of the crisis.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The limitations of a widely used financial model also were not properly understood.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This formula assumed that the price of CDS was correlated with and could predict the correct price of mortgage-backed securities.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Because it was highly tractable, it rapidly came to be used by a huge percentage of CDO and CDS investors, issuers, and rating agencies.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] As financial assets became more complex and harder to value, investors were reassured by the fact that the international bond rating agencies and bank regulators accepted as valid some complex mathematical models that showed the risks were much smaller than they actually were.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] George Soros commented that "The super-boom got out of hand when the new products became so complicated that the authorities could no longer calculate the risks and started relying on the risk management methods of the banks themselves.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Similarly, the rating agencies relied on the information provided by the originators of synthetic products.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] A conflict of interest between investment management professional and institutional investors, combined with a global glut in investment capital, led to bad investments by asset managers in over-priced credit assets.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Professional investment managers generally are compensated based on the volume of client assets under management.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] There is, therefore, an incentive for asset managers to expand their assets under management in order to maximize their compensation.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] As the glut in global investment capital caused the yields on credit assets to decline, asset managers were faced with the choice of either investing in assets where returns did not reflect true credit risk or returning funds to clients.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Many asset managers continued to invest client funds in over-priced (under-yielding) investments, to the detriment of their clients, so they could maintain their assets under management.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] They supported this choice with a "plausible deniability" of the risks associated with subprime-based credit assets because the loss experience with early "vintages" of subprime loans was so low.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Despite the dominance of the above formula, there are documented attempts of the financial industry, occurring before the crisis, to address the formula limitations, specifically the lack of dependence dynamics and the poor representation of extreme events.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The volume *Credit Correlation: Life After Copulas*, published in 2007 by World Scientific, summarizes a 2006 conference held by Merrill Lynch in London where several practitioners attempted to propose models rectifying some of the copula limitations.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] See also the article by Donnelly and Embrechts and the book by Brigo, Pallavicini and Torresetti, that reports relevant warnings and research on CDOs appeared in 2006.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] There is strong evidence that the riskiest, worst performing mortgages were funded through the "shadow banking system" and that competition from the shadow banking system may have pressured more traditional institutions to lower their underwriting standards and originate riskier loans.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] These entities became critical to the credit markets underpinning the financial system, but were not subject to the same regulatory controls.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Further, these entities were vulnerable because of asset–liability mismatch, meaning that they borrowed short-term in liquid markets to purchase long-term, illiquid and risky assets.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This meant that disruptions in credit markets would force them to engage in rapid deleveraging, selling their long-term assets at depressed prices.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Economist Paul Krugman, laureate of the Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences, described the run on the shadow banking system as the "core of what happened" to cause the crisis.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] He referred to this lack of controls as "malign neglect" and argued that regulation should have been imposed on all banking-like activity.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Without the ability to obtain investor funds in exchange for most types of mortgage-backed securities or asset-backed commercial paper, investment banks and other entities in the shadow banking system could not provide funds to mortgage firms and other corporations.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This meant that nearly one-third of the U.S. lending mechanism was frozen and continued to be frozen into June 2009.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] While traditional banks raised their lending standards, it was the collapse of the shadow banking system that was the primary cause of the reduction in funds available for borrowing.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Caballero, Emmanuel Farhi, and Pierre-Olivier Gourinchas argued that the financial crisis was attributable to "global asset scarcity, which led to large capital flows toward the United States and to the creation of asset bubbles that eventually burst".
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Long-only commodity index funds became popular – by one estimate investment increased from $90 billion in 2006 to $200 billion at the end of 2007, while commodity prices increased 71% – which raised concern as to whether these index funds caused the commodity bubble.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The cause of the global asset bubble can be partially attributable to the global savings glut.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] As theorized by Andrew Metrick, the demand for safe assets following the Asian Financial Crisis coupled with the lack of circulating treasuries created an unmet demand for "risk free" assets.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Thus, institutional investors like sovereign wealth funds and pension funds began purchasing synthetic safe assets like Triple-A Mortgage Backed Securities.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] As a consequence, the demand for so-called safe assets fueled the free flow of capital into housing in the United States.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This greatly worsened the crisis as banks and other financial institutions were incentivized to issue more mortgages than before.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Some commentators and economists associated with the Austrian School of economics, including former U.S.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Congressman Ron Paul and historian Tom Woods, have offered a libertarian interpretation of the crisis which differs from the explanations centered on deregulation and government oversight.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In Ron Paul's book, *End the Fed,* Paul argues that the Federal Reserve's prolonged policy of artificially low interest rates in the early 2000s created a credit bubble that allowed for speculative investments and unsustainable levels of debt, particularly in housing.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In Tom Woods' book *Meltdown*, he also contends that Federal Reserve manipulation of the money supply and credit markets distorted normal price signals, leading to widespread malinvestment, resulting in an inevitable correction.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Paul and Woods also criticized Fannie Mae's and Freddie Mac's role in the crisis, asserting that the entities engaged in excessive risk-taking by expanding homeownership beyond sustainable levels.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In doing this, the government intervention created moral hazard by assuring large financial institutions that they would receive government support in times of crisis, which Paul and Woods believe encouraged riskier behavior.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In a 1998 book, John McMurtry suggested that a financial crisis is a systemic crisis of capitalism itself.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In his 1978 book, *The Downfall of Capitalism and Communism*, Ravi Batra suggests that growing inequality of financial capitalism produces speculative bubbles that burst and result in depression and major political changes.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] He also suggested that a "demand gap" related to differing wage and productivity growth explains deficit and debt dynamics important to stock market developments.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] John Bellamy Foster, a political economy analyst and editor of the *Monthly Review*, believed that the decrease in GDP growth rates since the early 1970s is due to increasing market saturation.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Marxian economics followers Andrew Kliman, Michael Roberts, and Guglielmo Carchedi, in contradistinction to the *Monthly Review* school represented by Foster, pointed to capitalism's long-term tendency of the rate of profit to fall as the underlying cause of crises generally.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] From this point of view, the problem was the inability of capital to grow or accumulate at sufficient rates through productive investment alone.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Low rates of profit in productive sectors led to speculative investment in riskier assets, where there was potential for greater return on investment.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The speculative frenzy of the late 1990s and 2000s was, in this view, a consequence of a rising organic composition of capital, expressed through the fall in the rate of profit.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] According to Michael Roberts, the fall in the rate of profit "eventually triggered the credit crunch of 2007 when credit could no longer support profits".
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In 2005 book, *The Battle for the Soul of Capitalism*, John C.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Bogle wrote that "Corporate America went astray largely because the power of managers went virtually unchecked by our gatekeepers for far too long".
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In his book *The Big Mo*, Mark Roeder, a former executive at the Swiss-based UBS Bank, suggested that large-scale momentum, or The Big Mo, "played a pivotal role" in the financial crisis.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Roeder suggested that "recent technological advances, such as computer-driven trading programs, together with the increasingly interconnected nature of markets, has magnified the momentum effect.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Robert Reich attributed the economic downturn to the stagnation of wages in the United States, particularly those of the hourly workers who comprise 80% of the workforce.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This stagnation forced the population to borrow to meet the cost of living.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Economists Ailsa McKay and Margunn Bjørnholt argued that the financial crisis and the response to it revealed a crisis of ideas in mainstream economics and within the economics profession, and call for a reshaping of both the economy, economic theory and the economics profession.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] A report by the International Labour Organization concluded that cooperative banking institutions were less likely to fail than their competitors during the crisis.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The cooperative banking sector had 20% market share of the European banking sector, but accounted for only 7% of all the write-downs and losses between the third quarter of 2007 and first quarter of 2011.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In 2008, in the U.S., the rate of commercial bank failures was almost triple that of credit unions, and almost five times the credit union rate in 2010.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Credit unions increased their lending to small- and medium-sized businesses while overall lending to those businesses decreased.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Economists, particularly followers of mainstream economics, mostly failed to predict the crisis.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Several followers of heterodox economics predicted the crisis, with varying arguments.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Dirk Bezemer credits 12 economists with predicting the crisis: Dean Baker, Wynne Godley, Fred Harrison, Michael Hudson, Eric Janszen, Med Jones, Steve Keen, Jakob Broechner Madsen & Jens Kjaer Sørensen, Kurt Richebächer, Nouriel Roubini, Peter Schiff, and Robert Shiller.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Shiller, a founder of the Case–Shiller index that measures home prices, wrote an article a year before the collapse of Lehman Brothers in which he predicted that a slowing U.S. housing market would cause the housing bubble to burst, leading to financial collapse.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Peter Schiff regularly appeared on television in the years before the crisis and warned of the impending real estate collapse.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The Austrian School regarded the crisis as a vindication and classic example of a predictable credit-fueled bubble caused by laxity in monetary supply.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] There were other economists that did warn of a pending crisis.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The former Governor of the Reserve Bank of India, Raghuram Rajan, had predicted the crisis in 2005 when he became chief economist at the International Monetary Fund.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In 2005, at a celebration honoring Alan Greenspan, who was about to retire as chairman of the US Federal Reserve, Rajan delivered a controversial paper that was critical of the financial sector.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In that paper, Rajan "argued that disaster might loom".
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Rajan argued that financial sector managers were encouraged to "take risks that generate severe adverse consequences with small probability but, in return, offer generous compensation the rest of the time.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] He also took action against the establishment view by making a big financial bet on banking stocks and making a fortune from the crisis ("They didn't listen, so I took their money").
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Popular articles published in the mass media have led the general public to believe that the majority of economists have failed in their obligation to predict the financial crisis.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] For example, an article in *The New York Times* noted that economist Nouriel Roubini warned of such crisis as early as September 2006, and stated that the profession of economics is bad at predicting recessions.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] According to *The Guardian*, Roubini was ridiculed for predicting a collapse of the housing market and worldwide recession, while *The New York Times* labelled him "Dr.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In a 2012 article in the journal *Japan and the World Economy*, Andrew K.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Spiegel used a Multiple Indicator Multiple Cause (MIMIC) model on a cross-section of 107 countries to evaluate potential causes of the 2008 crisis.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The authors examined various economic indicators, ignoring contagion effects across countries.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Despite the fact that we use a wide number of possible causes in a flexible statistical framework, we are unable to link most of the commonly cited causes of the crisis to its incidence across countries.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The first visible institution to run into trouble in the United States was the Southern California–based IndyMac, a spin-off of Countrywide Financial.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Before its failure, IndyMac Bank was the largest savings and loan association in the Los Angeles market and the seventh-largest mortgage loan originator in the United States.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The failure of IndyMac Bank on July 11, 2008, was (until the crisis precipitated even larger failures) the fourth-largest bank failure in United States history, and the second-largest failure of a regulated thrift.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac Bank's parent corporation was IndyMac Bancorp until the FDIC seized IndyMac Bank.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac Bancorp filed for Chapter 7 bankruptcy in July 2008.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac Bank was founded as Countrywide Mortgage Investment in 1985 by David S.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Loeb and Angelo Mozilo as a means of collateralizing Countrywide Financial loans too big to be sold to Freddie Mac and Fannie Mae.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In 1997, Countrywide spun off IndyMac as an independent company run by Mike Perry, who remained its CEO until the downfall of the bank in July 2008.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The primary causes of its failure were largely associated with its business strategy of originating and securitizing Alt-A loans on a large scale.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This strategy resulted in rapid growth and a high concentration of risky assets.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] From its inception as a savings association in 2000, IndyMac grew to the seventh largest savings and loan and ninth largest originator of mortgage loans in the United States.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] During 2006, IndyMac originated over $90 billion (~$134 billion in 2024) of mortgages.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac often made loans without verification of the borrower's income or assets, and to borrowers with poor credit histories.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Appraisals obtained by IndyMac on underlying collateral were often questionable as well.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] As an Alt-A lender, IndyMac's business model was to offer loan products to fit the borrower's needs, using an extensive array of risky option-adjustable-rate mortgages (option ARMs), subprime loans, 80/20 loans, and other nontraditional products.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Ultimately, loans were made to many borrowers who simply could not afford to make their payments.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The thrift remained profitable only as long as it was able to sell those loans in the secondary mortgage market.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac resisted efforts to regulate its involvement in those loans or tighten their issuing criteria: see the comment by Ruthann Melbourne, Chief Risk Officer, to the regulating agencies.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] On May 12, 2008, in the "Capital" section of its last 10-Q, IndyMac revealed that it may not be well capitalized in the future.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac reported that during April 2008, Moody's and Standard & Poor's downgraded the ratings on a significant number of Mortgage-backed security (MBS) bonds—including $160 million (~$228 million in 2024) issued by IndyMac that the bank retained in its MBS portfolio.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac concluded that these downgrades would have harmed its risk-based capital ratio as of June 30, 2008.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Had these lowered ratings been in effect on March 31, 2008, IndyMac concluded that the bank's capital ratio would have been 9.27% total risk-based.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac warned that if its regulators found its capital position to have fallen below "well capitalized" (minimum 10% risk-based capital ratio) to "adequately capitalized" (8–10% risk-based capital ratio) the bank might no longer be able to use brokered deposits as a source of funds.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Senator Charles Schumer (D-NY) later pointed out that brokered deposits made up more than 37% of IndyMac's total deposits, and asked the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation (FDIC) whether it had considered ordering IndyMac to reduce its reliance on these deposits.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] With $18.9 billion in total deposits reported on March 31, Senator Schumer would have been referring to a little over $7 billion in brokered deposits.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] While the breakout of maturities of these deposits is not known exactly, a simple averaging would have put the threat of brokered deposits loss to IndyMac at $500 million a month, had the regulator disallowed IndyMac from acquiring new brokered deposits on June 30.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac was taking new measures to preserve capital, such as deferring interest payments on some preferred securities.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Dividends on common shares had already been suspended for the first quarter of 2008, after being cut in half the previous quarter.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The company still had not secured a significant capital infusion nor found a ready buyer.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac reported that the bank's risk-based capital was only $47 million above the minimum required for this 10% mark.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] But it did not reveal some of that $47 million (~$67 million in 2024) capital it claimed it had, as of March 31, 2008, was fabricated.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] When home prices declined in the latter half of 2007 and the secondary mortgage market collapsed, IndyMac was forced to hold $10.7 billion (~$15.5 billion in 2024) of loans it could not sell in the secondary market.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Its reduced liquidity was further exacerbated in late June 2008 when account holders withdrew $1.55 billion (~$2.21 billion in 2024) or about 7.5% of IndyMac's deposits.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This bank run on the thrift followed the public release of a letter from Senator Charles Schumer to the FDIC and OTS.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The letter outlined the Senator's concerns with IndyMac.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] While the run was a contributing factor in the timing of IndyMac's demise, the underlying cause of the failure was the unsafe and unsound way it was operated.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac announced the closure of both its retail lending and wholesale divisions, halted new loan submissions, and cut 3,800 jobs.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] On July 11, 2008, citing liquidity concerns, the FDIC put IndyMac Bank into conservatorship.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] A bridge bank, IndyMac Federal Bank, FSB, was established to assume control of IndyMac Bank's assets, its secured liabilities, and its insured deposit accounts.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The FDIC announced plans to open IndyMac Federal Bank, FSB on July 14, 2008.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Until then, depositors would have access to their insured deposits through ATMs, their existing checks, and their existing debit cards.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Telephone and Internet account access was restored when the bank reopened.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The FDIC guarantees the funds of all insured accounts up to US$100,000, and declared a special advance dividend to the roughly 10,000 depositors with funds in excess of the insured amount, guaranteeing 50% of any amounts in excess of $100,000.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Yet, even with the pending sale of Indymac to IMB Management Holdings, an estimated 10,000 uninsured depositors of Indymac are still at a loss of over $270 million.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] With $32 billion in assets, IndyMac Bank was one of the largest bank failures in American history.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac Bancorp filed for Chapter 7 bankruptcy on July 31, 2008.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Initially the companies affected were those directly involved in home construction and mortgage lending such as Northern Rock and Countrywide Financial, as they could no longer obtain financing through the credit markets.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Over 100 mortgage lenders went bankrupt during 2007 and 2008.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Concerns that investment bank Bear Stearns would collapse in March 2008 resulted in its fire-sale to JP Morgan Chase.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The financial institution crisis hit its peak in September and October 2008.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Several major institutions either failed, were acquired under duress, or were subject to government takeover.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] These included Lehman Brothers, Merrill Lynch, Fannie Mae, Freddie Mac, Washington Mutual, Wachovia, Citigroup, and AIG.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] On October 6, 2008, three weeks after Lehman Brothers filed the largest bankruptcy in U.S. history, Lehman's former CEO Richard S.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Fuld Jr. found himself before Representative Henry A.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Waxman, the California Democrat who chaired the House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform.
[src:brittany/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Fuld said he was a victim of the collapse, blaming a "crisis of confidence" in the markets for dooming his firm.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] The **5th millennium BC** spanned the years 5000 BC to 4001 BC.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] It is impossible to precisely date events that happened around the time of this millennium and all dates mentioned here are estimates mostly based on geological and anthropological analysis.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] The rapid world population growth of the previous millennium, caused by the Neolithic Revolution, is believed to have slowed and become fairly stable.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] It has been estimated that there were around forty million people worldwide by 5000 BC, growing to 100 million by the Middle Bronze Age c.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] The Stentinello culture stretches from Sicily and Calabria to the Aeolian Islands representing cultural focus on seafaring and maritime trade at this time.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] Sardinia has close trade relations with the Mediterranean Neolithic communities of southern France, the Iberian Peninsula, the Italian peninsula and Sicily and is a major participant of the silver trade.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] Overall, the Ubaid period experiences sporadic but controlled growth of socially stratified settlements, with communal areas, segregation of classes per quarters and complex social stratification.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] Increased conflict between democratic councils, large scale chiefdoms, royalties, polities and imperial-like aspirations.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] Large scale stone masonry for public use, and organised seal estampage of international importance are associated characteristics of the era.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] Amiet sees as a 'proto-royal figure,' i.e., potentially Enki, preceding the 'priest-kings' of the 4th millennium.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] In modern Turkey: Strong Anatolian polities counteract the balance of power from the Ubaid polities and dwaining Samarrans who were culturally assimilated around 4800 BC.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] Such polities include Mersin notably having a standing army circa 4300 BC, and Hamoukar, which was a major production centre in the important Obsidian trade and thus power.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] An intensive copper trade, connecting Europe with the East, is represented in Anatolia by sites at Hacilar, Beycesultan, Canhasan, Mersin Yumuktepe, Elazig Tepecik, Malatya Degirmentepe, Norşuntepe, and Istanbul Fikirtepe.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] Prior environmental devastation in the previous two millennia may account for the lack of Neolithic sites in northern Turkey.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] In the Levant: Ghassulian culture thrives, immigrating from the North into the whole of the Levant circa 4400 BC.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] With concentrated settlements and elites economically focused on copper metallurgy and trade, notably importing from Southern Jordan's vast and powerful urban polities and Bedouin-like cultures.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] This Sotira culture replaced the void of the collapse of the 6th millennium Neolithic culture in Cyprus.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] Trade with Levant and external regions on an impressive scale and covering large distances starts to connect Europe with Asia on a more direct scale than before.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] Obsidian found in the Chalcolithic levels at Gilat, Israel have had their origins traced via elemental analysis to three sources in Southern Anatolia: Hotamis Dağ, Göllü Dağ, and as far east as Nemrut Dağ, 500 km (310 mi) east of the other two sources.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] This is indicative of a very large trade circle reaching as far as the Northern Fertile Crescent and Anatolia.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] In the Caucasus: Settlements of the 5th millennium BC in North Caucasus attest to a material culture that was related to contemporaneous archaeological complexes in the northern and western Black Sea region like the Leyla-Tepe culture (c.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] These polities were immense economically, and pioneered copper metallurgy and trade.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] Constant immigration from Ubadians and from Uruk herself did play economic factors as well.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] Such cultural elements change and are replaced, suddenly during the latter first half of the 4th Millennium BC, and the quality of copper metallurgy declines somewhat, during the Kura–Araxes culture.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] On the other hand, the millennia long attested Shulaveri–Shomu culture showed stronger cultural connections like similar tool kits and use of red ochre, portrays intimate and centuries-old ties with the Halafians.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] In Arabia: Continuation of Ubaid economical expansion and culture(since the 6th millennium BC, circa 5500 BC) throughout Arabia, with adoption and integration but also contributions to these new political features.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] Ubaid pottery of periods 2 and 3 has been documented at site H3 in Kuwait and in Dosariyah in eastern Saudi Arabia, which bordered the Persian Gulf, a major trade hub.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] Significant linguistic connections are made with the precursor to the Proto-Indo European languages (circa 4500 BC), via the Eurasiatic language and parts of the Dravidian language to a prior language family during the Upper Palaeolithic.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] Dravidian having multiple cultural origins and development over millennia can be considered just as influential on an international scale as the Indo European languages from the 5th millennium BC to the 1st millennium AD.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] Such influence has been explored, such examples are the Elamo-Dravidian languages, a family that would have pioneered Susa, Central Mesopotamia, trade and politics within the Ubaid era.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] These Southern migrations into India contributed to parts of the Proto-Dravidian language, having multiple variants i.e., Proto-South Dravidian language based on geographical location, however the language itself is known to have largely been native to central India as well.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] This melting pot of cultures peaked from the 5th millennium BC into the 4th millennium BC.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] Chinese civilisation advanced in this millennium with the beginnings of three noted cultures from around 5000 BC.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] The Yangshao culture was based in the Huang He (Yellow River) basin and endured for some 2,000 years.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] It is believed that pigs were first domesticated there.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] Pottery was fired in kilns dug into the ground and then painted.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] A type-site settlement for the Yangshao was established c.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] 4700 BC at Banpo near modern Xi'an, Shaanxi.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] Also about 5000 BC, the Hemudu culture began in eastern China with cultivation of rice, and the Majiabang culture was established on the Yangtze estuary near modern Shanghai, lasting until c.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] It is estimated that the distinctive Aboriginal rock carvings near Sydney were created sometime between 5000 BC and 3000 BC.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] Sea levels had become relatively stabilized by the time of 4500 BC around the coastlines of Australia.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] This occurred after several thousands of years of sea level rising, due to glaciers melting after the Younger Dryas event.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] This knowledge was passed down in oral history among the Aboriginal tribes of Australia as they recalled the drastic sea level rises that ended up swallowing their once lower coastlines.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] Around the time of the 5th Millennium BC, there was a proliferation of stone tool, plant processing and landscape modification technologies.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] Elaborate fish and eel traps involving channels up to three kilometres long were in use in western Victoria from about 6,500 years ago.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] Semi-permanent collections of wooden huts on mounds also appeared in western Victoria, associated with a more systematic exploitation of new food sources in the wetlands.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] The Furneaux Group, which is a set of islands off the Northeast portion of Tasmania, had been inhabited since at least 33,000 BC, but the Aboriginal Tasmanians stopped living there permanently around the time of 4,000 BC.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] Rock art in the Northern Territory of Australia, specifically from the area of Arnhem Land is said to have a portion of its depictions dating to around 4,000 BC, which show battle scenes or skirmishes between the people in the local area.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] The art also includes animals and other ceremonial meanings.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] These scenes have been dated to up to 10,000 years old and down to 6,000 years old when painted continuously over time.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] Stone points for spears and distinct stone point technology have been found dating from 5–7 thousand years ago in Australia.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] Many of the early stone point technologies are specifically found in the Kimberley Region of north-western Australia.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] Spear-launching devices, such as the woomera are believed to have entered widespread use at around this time.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] More complex structures followed during a second intensive wave onwards from 4500 BC.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] With alignments with Sirius, Arcturus, Alpha Centauri, and the Belt of Orion.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] This suggests a great academic pursuit to investigate astronomical observations, cosmology and mathematics.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] Fifth millennium alignments of stele to bright stars focussed on issues of major practical importance of the era being: cattle, water, death, earth, sun, stars and theology.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] Shell mounds in these areas are highly visible, which likely aided in their identification by scholars.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] Examples like Cerro de las Conchas, which dates between 5500 and 3500BC appearing to have been a sea resource collection and processing site.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] While it seems Cerro de las Conchas was only occupied seasonally, it seems likely that inland base camps were occupied year-round.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] Lauricocha III: 4200 – 2500 BC (Andean preceramic V) begins.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] Chiefdoms and fish gatherer-hunter societies dominate.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] Lauricocha was one of the important mountain encampments at the time.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] The 5th millennium has become a start point for calendars and chronologies.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] The year 4750 BC is the retrospective startpoint for the Assyrian calendar, marking the traditional date for the foundation of Assur, some 2,000 years before it actually happened.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] Another traditional date is 19 July 4241 BC, marking the supposed beginning of the Egyptian calendar, as calculated retrospectively by Eduard Meyer.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] The more likely startpoint is 19 July 2781 BC, one Sothic cycle later.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] It has generally been believed that the calendar was based on a heliacal (dawn) rising of Sirius but that view is now being questioned.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] According to the Ussher chronology, the creation of Earth happened on 22/23 October 4004 BC.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] This chronology was the work of James Ussher, whose basis was the dates in the Old Testament of the Bible.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] He estimated that the universe was created by God at either 18:00 on the 22nd (Jewish calendar) or 09:00 on the 23rd (Ussher-Lightfoot-Chronology).
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] Yet another calendar starting date in the 5th millennium is Monday, 1 January 4713 BC, the beginning of the current Julian Period, first described by Joseph Justus Scaliger in the sixteenth century.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] This Julian Period lasts 7,980 years until the year 3268 (current era) in the next millennium.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] It is a useful device for date conversions between different calendars.
[src:brittany/5th-millennium-bc] The date of origin has the integer value of zero in the Julian Day Count: i.e., in the Julian Calendar; the equivalent date in the Gregorian Calendar is 24 November 4714 BC.
[src:brittany/a11-autoroute] The **A 11 autoroute** is a motorway which connects Paris with Nantes via Le Mans and Angers.
[src:brittany/a11-autoroute] The road is 323 kilometres (201 mi) long.
[src:brittany/a11-autoroute] The following list indexes the sites worth visiting within 14 km of the road.
[src:brittany/a81-autoroute] The **A81 autoroute** is a motorway in north-western France.
[src:brittany/a81-autoroute] It forms the first part of a long-term project to upgrade the road connection between Le Mans and Brest to motorway standard throughout.
[src:brittany/a81-autoroute] Until 1982 the motorway was known as the F11.
[src:brittany/a81-autoroute] The A81 is a part of European route E50 linking Brest to Makhachkala in Russia.
[src:brittany/a84-autoroute] The **A84 autoroute** is a major motorway in western France completed on 27 January 2003 to connect the cities of Rennes in Brittany with Caen in Lower Normandy.
[src:brittany/a84-autoroute] It is part of the *Autoroute des Estuaires* from Belgium to Spain, avoiding Paris.
[src:brittany/a84-autoroute] The motorway, 170 km long, cost a total of € 650 million.
[src:brittany/a84-autoroute] It is dual-carriageway both ways on its entire course and service areas are positioned at regular intervals.
[src:brittany/a84-autoroute] The motorway was built with a special road surface to allow rain water to run off quickly, but it is ineffective with snow that often falls in large quantities in winter, so snowploughs are employed regularly.
[src:brittany/a84-autoroute] Motorway traffic radio 107.7 broadcasts A84 information specifically.
[src:brittany/a84-autoroute] The highway is free throughout its entire length.
[src:brittany/a84-autoroute] The various governments have studied the concession of this highway, but the regional authorities of Brittany and Normandy have convinced the public authorities to build and manage this highway with public funds.
[src:brittany/a84-autoroute] The Autoroute is served by the following four Village étapes, Ducey, Maen Roch, Torigny-les-Villes and Villers-Bocage.
[src:brittany/a84-autoroute] The bypass to the west of Avranches, by the RN 175 with two double lanes, has geometrical characteristics which do not allow the construction of motorway characteristics and status.
[src:brittany/a84-autoroute] An East motorway bypass for the A84 was therefore planned in the long term.
[src:brittany/a84-autoroute] The State bought 60 hectares of land and destroyed four houses along the route.
[src:brittany/a84-autoroute] The A84 is also to be extended to Nantes by upgrading the RN 137 dual-carriageway, thus creating a Caen-Rennes-Nantes route.
[src:brittany/a84-autoroute] This was abandoned, along with other projects of dual-carriageway upgrades in Brittany (RN 157 and RN 12 were planned to become A81 and RN 165 was planned to become A82).
[src:brittany/a84-autoroute] In addition at Rennes, the construction of a "south-east bypass" will make it possible to avoid the Rennes ring-road on this route.
[src:brittany/a84-autoroute] Construction was due to commence from 2021 but was abandoned.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The region had autonomy as the Abkhaz Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic within the Georgian Soviet Socialist Republic at the time when the Soviet Union began to disintegrate in the late 1980s.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The political status of Abkhazia is the central issue of the Abkhazia conflict and Georgia–Russia relations.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Abkhazia is formally recognised as an independent state by five UN member states (Russia, Venezuela, Nicaragua, Nauru, and Syria), with two other states having previously recognised but withdrawn their recognition (Tuvalu and Vanuatu).
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The remainder of the international community recognises Abkhazia as *de jure* part of Georgia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Lacking effective control over the Abkhazian territory, Georgia maintains an Abkhaz government-in-exile.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Despite a 1994 ceasefire agreement and years of negotiations, the dispute remains unresolved.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The long-term presence of a United Nations Observer Mission and a Russian-led Commonwealth of Independent States peacekeeping force failed to prevent the flare-up of violence on several occasions.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] In August 2008, Abkhaz and Russian forces fought the Russo-Georgian War against Georgian forces, which led to the formal recognition of Abkhazia by Russia, the annulment of the 1994 ceasefire agreement and the termination of the UN mission.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] On 23 October 2008, the Parliament of Georgia declared Abkhazia a Russian-occupied territory.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The Russian name Абхазия (**Abkhaziya**) is adapted from the Georgian აფხაზეთი (**Apkhazeti**).
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The Abkhaz name *Apsny* (Abkhaz: Аԥсны, IPA [apʰsˈnɨ]) is etymologised as 'a land of the soul'; however, the literal meaning is 'a country of mortals'.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] It possibly first appeared in the seventh century in an Armenian text, perhaps referring to the ancient Apsilians.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] In early Muslim sources, the term *Abkhazia* was generally used to mean the territory of Georgia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Presumably considered as a successor of the Kingdom of *Laziǩa* (*Egrisi* in Georgian sources), this new polity continued to be referred to as *Egrisi* in some Byzantine era Georgian and Armenian chronicles (e.g.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] *The Vitae of the Georgian Kings* by Leonti Mroveli and *History of Armenia* by Hovhannes Draskhanakerttsi).
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The Constitution of Abkhazia says the names of the "Republic of Abkhazia" and "Apsny" are equivalent and interchangeable.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Before the 20th century, the region was sometimes referred to in English language sources as *Abhasia*.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Between the 9th and 6th centuries BC, the territory of modern Abkhazia was part of the ancient Kingdom of Colchis.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Around the 6th century BC, the Greeks established trade colonies along the Black Sea coast of present-day Abkhazia, in particular at Pitiunt and Dioscurias.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Classical authors described various peoples living in the region and the great multitude of languages they spoke.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Arrian, Pliny and Strabo have given accounts of the Abasgoi and Moschoi peoples somewhere in modern Abkhazia on the eastern shore of the Black Sea.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] This region was subsequently absorbed in 63 BC into the Kingdom of *Laziǩa*.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] According to an Eastern tradition, Simon the Zealot died in Abkhazia during a missionary trip and was buried in Nicopsis; his mortal remains were later transferred to Anacopia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The Roman Empire conquered Lazica in the 1st century AD; however, the Roman presence was confined to port cities.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] According to Arrian, the Abasgoi and Apsilae peoples were nominal Roman subjects, and there was a small Roman outpost in Dioscurias.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Abasgoi likely served in the Roman army in *Ala Prima Abasgorum*, which was stationed in Egypt.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] After the 4th century Lazica regained a measure of independence, but remained within the Byzantine Empire's sphere of influence.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Anacopia was the principality's capital.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The country was mostly Christian, with the archbishop's seat in Pityus.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Stratophilus, the Metropolitan of Pityus, participated in the First Council of Nicaea in 325.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Around the middle of the 6th century AD, the Byzantines and the neighbouring Sassanid Persia fought for supremacy over Abkhazia, a conflict known as the Lazic War.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] During the war the Abasgians revolted against the Byzantine Empire and requested Sasanian assistance; the revolt was suppressed by General Bessas.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] An Arab incursion into Abasgia, led by Marwan II, was repelled by Prince Leon I jointly with his Lazic and Iberian allies in 736.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Leon I then married Mirian's daughter and a successor, King Leon II exploited this dynastic union to acquire Lazica in the 770s.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The successful defence against the Arab Caliphate, and new territorial gains in the east gave the Abasgian princes enough power to claim more autonomy from the Byzantine Empire.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Circa 778, Prince Leon II, with the help of the Khazars, declared independence from the Byzantine Empire and transferred his residence to Kutaisi.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] During this period the Georgian language replaced Greek as the language of literacy and culture.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The Kingdom of Abkhazia flourished between 850 and 950 AD, which ended by unification of Abkhazia and eastern Georgian states under a single Georgian monarchy ruled by King Bagrat III at the end of the 10th century and the beginning of the 11th century.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] During the reign of Queen Tamar, Georgian chronicles mention Otagho as the Eristavi of Abkhazia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] He was one of the first representatives of the House of Shervashidze (also known as Chachba) which went on to rule Abkhazia until the 19th century.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] In the 1240s, Mongols divided Georgia into eight military-administrative sectors (tümens).
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The territory of contemporary Abkhazia formed part of the tümen administered by Tsotne Dadiani.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] In the 16th century, after the break-up of the Georgian Kingdom into small kingdoms and principalities, the Principality of Abkhazia (nominally a vassal of the Kingdom of Imereti) emerged, ruled by the Shervashidze dynasty.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] In 1453, the Ottomans first attacked Sukhumi, and in the 1570s, they had a garrison there.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Throughout the 17th century, they continued to launch attacks, leading to the imposition of tribute on Abkhazia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Ottoman influence grew significantly in the 18th century with the construction of a fort in Sukhumi, accompanied by a conversion of the rulers of Abkhazia and many other Abkhaz to Islam.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Nonetheless, conflicts between the Abkhaz and Turks persisted.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The spread of Islam in Abkhazia was first evidenced by the Ottoman traveller Evliya Çelebi in 1641.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Despite this, the Islamisation was more evident in the higher levels of society rather than the general population.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] In his work, Çelebi also wrote that the principal tribe of the Abkhazian principality, Chách, spoke the Mingrelian language, a subset of Kartvelian (Georgian) languages.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Abkhazia sought protection from the Russian Empire in 1801 but was declared "an autonomous principality" by the Russians in 1810.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Russia then annexed Abkhazia in 1864, and Abkhaz resistance was quashed as the Russians deported Muslim Abkhaz to Ottoman territories.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] In the beginning of the 19th century, while the Russians and Ottomans were vying for control of the region, the rulers of Abkhazia shifted back and forth across the religious divide.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The first attempt to enter into relations with Russia was made by Prince Kelesh-Bey in 1803, shortly after the incorporation of eastern Georgia into the expanding Tsarist empire in 1801.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] However, pro-Ottoman sympathy in Abkhazia prevailed for a short time after Kelesh-Bey was assassinated by his son, Aslan-Bey, in 1801.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] On 2 July 1810, Russian Marines stormed Sukhum-Kale and had Aslan-Bey replaced with his rival and brother, Sefer Ali-Bey, who had converted to Christianity and assumed the name of George.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Abkhazia joined the Russian Empire as an autonomous principality, in 1810.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] However, Sefer-bey's rule was limited and many mountain regions were as independent as before.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The next Russo-Turkish war (1828–1829) strongly enhanced the Russian positions, leading to a further split in the Abkhaz elite, mainly along religious divisions.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] During the Crimean War (1853–1856), Russian forces had to evacuate Abkhazia and Prince Hamud-Bey Sharvashidze-Chachba (Mikhail), who ruled from 1822 to 1864, seemingly switched to the Ottomans.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Later on, the Russian presence strengthened and the highlanders of Western Caucasia were finally subjugated by Russia in 1864.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Later that same year, Abkhazia was incorporated into the Russian Empire as a special military province of Sukhum-Kale which was transformed, in 1883, into an *okrug* as part of the Kutaisi Governorate.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Large numbers of Muslim Abkhazians, said to have constituted as much as 40% of the Abkhazian population, emigrated to the Ottoman Empire between 1864 and 1878 together with other Muslim populations of the Caucasus, a process known as *Muhajirism*.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Large areas of the region were left uninhabited and many Armenians, Georgians, Russians and others subsequently migrated to Abkhazia, resettling much of the vacated territory.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Some Georgian historians assert that Georgian tribes (Svans and Mingrelians) had populated Abkhazia since the time of the Colchis kingdom.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The Russian government had plans to colonize Abkhazia with Russian settlers, and created a special legal framework granting land allocations to Russians to encourage their migration.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] However, the Russian colonization efforts failed because of the lack of roads connecting Abkhazia to the main economic centers in Southern Russia, the unfamiliarity of the Russian settlers with local climate and agriculture, and their high susceptibility to malaria (leading to some deaths).
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] This led to the other ethnic groups, which the Russian government did not plan to be settled in Abkhazia, to migrate spontaneously and outnumber the Russians in the region.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] This included former Ottoman subjects, such as Greeks and Armenians, and Mingrelians from the neighboring province within the empire.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Both were more familiar with the local climate and were less susceptible to malaria.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The Mingrelians became the largest group of arrivals, despite being marginalized as an agricultural labor force due to the lack of state support and legal restrains placed on them.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Their arrival alarmed the Russian authorities, because they saw the Mingrelian migration as an impediment to the Russian colonization, and the Russian government responded with the legal measures to restrict the settlement of Mingrelians in Abkhazia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The same policy was conducted to alienate Abkhazians from Georgians despite their common historical heritage and few problems historically.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] In the case of the Abkhaz, Russia attempted to obviate the use of the Georgian language by Abkhazians which they previously wielded as the second language and used for the literacy and high culture.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Instead, the Russian authorities put an effort to substitute Georgian with the Russian language.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] A separate Abkhaz alphabet was created based on Cyrillic script and the teaching of the Russian language to Abkhazians was mandated.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] By official decision of the Russian authorities, the residents of Abkhazia and Samurzakano had to study and pray in Russian.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] After the mass deportation of 1878, Abkhazians were left in the minority, officially branded "guilty people", and had no leader capable of mounting serious opposition to Russification.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] On 17 March 1898, the synodal department of the Russian Orthodox Church of Georgia-Imereti, by Order 2771, again prohibited teaching and the conduct of religious services in Georgian.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Mass protests by the Georgian population of Abkhazia and Samurzakano followed, news of which reached the Russian emperor.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] On 3 September 1898 the Holy Synod issued Order 4880, which decreed that those parishes where the congregation was Mingrelian (i.e.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Georgian), conduct both church services and church education in Georgian, while Abkhazian parishes use old Slavic.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] In the Sukhumi district, this order was carried out in only three of 42 parishes.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Tedo Sakhokia demanded the Russian authorities introduce Abkhazian and Georgian languages in church services and education.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The official response was a criminal case brought against Tedo Sakhokia and leaders of his "Georgian Party" active in Abkhazia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] In 1904, the territory of Gagra District was detached from Sukhumi okrug and joined to the Black Sea Governorate after Duke Alexander of Oldenburg, a member of the Russian royalty, built a resort there.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] By the early 20th century, the Georgians, represented by Samurzakanians and Mingrelians, were the largest group in Abkhazia, but from the social point of view, they were the most disadvantaged and marginalized group, being agricultural workers with severe restrictions on their residential status.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The Abkhaz and the Russians were the well-off groups which controlled large amounts of land and were well-represented in the nobility and bureaucracy.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Armenians and Greeks were mostly involved in the tobacco industry.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Following the October Revolution in Russia, the Transcaucasian Commissariat was set up in Southern Caucasus, which gradually took steps towards the independence.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Transcaucasia declared its independence from Russia on 9 April 1918 as a federative republic.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] On 8 May 1918, the Bolsheviks seized power in Abkhazia and disbanded the local Abkhaz People's Council.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] It requested aid from the Transcausian authorities, which dispatched the Georgian People's Guard and defeated the rebels on 17 May.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] On 26 May 1918, Georgia declared independence from the Transcaucasian Federation, which dissolved on 28 May.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] On 8 June 1918, the Abkhaz People's Council signed a treaty with the Georgian National Council, which confirmed Abkhazia's status as an autonomy within the Georgian Democratic Republic.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The Georgian army defeated another Bolshevik rebellion in the region.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] It remained part of Georgia after another Bolshevik revolt and a Turkish expedition were defeated in 1918.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The Russian general and a leader of White movement Anton Denikin laid claims on Abkhazia and captured Gagra, but the Georgians counter-attacked in April 1919 and retook the city.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Denikin's Volunteer Army was eventually defeated by the Red Army, and Bolshevik Russia signed an agreement with Georgia in May 1920, recognising Abkhazia as a part of Georgia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] In 1919, a first election was held to the Abkhaz People's Council.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The Council favoured being an autonomous region within Georgia, and it lasted until the Red Army invasion of Georgia in February 1921.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] On 20 March 1919, the newly elected Abkhazian People's Council adopted the "Act on Abkhazian Autonomy", which formalised the establishment of the Abkhazian Autonomy within the Georgian Democratic Republic.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] In 1921, the Bolshevik Red Army invaded Georgia and ended its short-lived independence.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Abkhazia was made a Socialist Soviet Republic (SSR Abkhazia) with the ambiguous status of a "*treaty republic"* associated with the Georgian SSR.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Under the *korenizatsiia* policy of the Soviet Union, the Abkhaz people were not considered the "advanced" people, and thus saw an increased focus on their national language and cultural development.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Under this nationalities policy, the Abkhaz received various benefits such as schooling in their language; the official literary language was established for the first time.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Between 1922 and 1926, the share of Abkhazes increased from 19.8% to 27.8% of the population (possibly due to the immigration of ethnic Abkhaz from Turkey or re-identification as Abkhaz).
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Their share among the members of the local communist party grew from 10% to the 25%.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Meanwhile, the proportion of the ethnic Georgian population decreased from 42% in 1922 to 36% in 1926, while their proportion in the local communist party also decreased from 40% to 33%.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The report noted that all major posts were held by the Abkhaz, they were overrepresented in the local structures such as the police, and the local Komsomol was only admitting ethnic Abkhazians.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] In 1931, Joseph Stalin made Abkhazia an autonomous republic (Abkhaz ASSR) within the Georgian SSR.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] In the Terror of 1937–38, the ruling elite was purged of Abkhazes and by 1952 over 80% of the 228 top party and government officials and enterprise managers were ethnic Georgians; there remained 34 Abkhazes, 7 Russians, and 3 Armenians in these positions.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Georgian Communist Party leader Kandid Charkviani supported the Georgianization of Abkhazia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Starting from 1939, peasant households from the rest of the Georgian SSR were resettled to Abkhazia which changed its demographic makeup significantly.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Georgians were the largest ethnic group in Abkhazia even before Stalin's policies.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The publishing of materials in Abkhazian dwindled and was eventually stopped altogether; Abkhaz schools were closed in 1945–1946, requiring Abkhaz children to study in the Georgian language.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The teaching of the Abkhaz language was preserved in the new reorganised Abkhaz schools as a mandatory subject by the decision of the Georgian Communist Party.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The policy of repression was eased after Stalin's death and Beria's execution, and the Abkhaz were given a greater role in the governance of the republic.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] As in most of the smaller autonomous republics, the Soviet government encouraged the development of culture and particularly of literature.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The Abkhazian ASSR was the only autonomous republic in the USSR in which the language of the titular nation (in that case Abkhaz) was confirmed in its constitution as one of its official languages.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] In the post-war period, the Abkhazian ASSR was dominated by the ethnic Abkhazes, who occupied many more positions in the autonomous republic compared to Georgians.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] During the late Soviet period, ethnic Abkhazes occupied 41% of the seats in Abkhazian Supreme Soviet, and 67% of the republican ministers were ethnically Abkhaz.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Moreover, they held even larger proportion of lower level official posts within the autonomous republic.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The first secretary of the communist party in Abkhazia was also ethnically Abkhaz.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] All of this was despite the fact that Abkhazians made up only 17.8% of the region's population, while Georgians made up 45.7%, and other ethnicities (Greeks, Russians, Armenians, etc.) made up 36.5%.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] As the Soviet Union began to disintegrate at the end of the 1980s, ethnic tensions grew between the Abkhaz and Georgians over Georgia's moves towards independence.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Many Abkhaz opposed this, fearing that an independent Georgia would lead to the elimination of their autonomy, and argued instead for the establishment of Abkhazia as a separate Soviet republic in its own right.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] With the onset of perestroika, the agenda of Abkhaz nationalists became more radical and exclusive.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] In 1988, they began to ask for the reinstatement of Abkhazia's former status of Union Republic, as the submission of Abkhazia to another Union Republic was not considered to give enough guarantees of their development.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] They justified their request by referring to the Leninist tradition of the right of nations to self-determination, which they asserted was violated when Abkhazia's sovereignty was curtailed in 1931.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] In June 1988, a manifesto defending Abkhaz distinctiveness (known as the Abkhazian Letter) was sent to Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The Georgian–Abkhaz dispute turned violent on 16 July 1989 in Sukhumi.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Numerous Georgians were killed or injured when they tried to enroll in a Georgian university instead of an Abkhaz one.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] After several days of violence, Soviet troops restored order in the city.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] In March 1990, Georgia declared sovereignty, unilaterally nullifying treaties concluded by the Soviet government since 1921 and thereby moving closer to independence.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Most ethnic non-Georgians in Abkhazia later boycotted a 31 March referendum on Georgia's independence, which was supported by a huge majority of Georgian population.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Within weeks, Georgia declared independence on 9 April 1991, under former Soviet dissident Zviad Gamsakhurdia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Under Gamsakhurdia, the situation was relatively calm in Abkhazia and a power-sharing agreement was soon reached between the Abkhaz and Georgian factions, granting to the Abkhaz a certain over-representation in the local legislature.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Under the compromise solution negotiated in August 1991, the Abkhaz received an ethnic quota of 28 seats in the Abkhazian Supreme Soviet, despite being only 18% of the population.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The Georgians, making up 46% of the population, got 26 seats, while the rest received 11 seats.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] A two-thirds majority was to be required to pass constitutional changes to ensure that key decisions would not be taken without approval from both Abkhaz and Georgian deputies and each side would hold veto power in principle.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The elections using this scheme were held in late 1991.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Gamsakhurdia's rule was soon challenged by armed opposition groups, under the command of Tengiz Kitovani, that forced him to flee the country in a military coup in January 1992.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Gamsakhurdia was replaced by former Soviet Georgian leader and Soviet foreign minister Eduard Shevardnadze, who became the country's head of state.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] On 21 February 1992, Georgia's ruling military council announced that it was abolishing the Soviet-era constitution and restoring the 1921 Constitution of the Democratic Republic of Georgia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Many Abkhaz interpreted this as an abolition of their autonomous status, although the 1921 constitution contained a provision for the region's autonomy.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] On 23 July 1992, the Abkhaz faction in the republic's Supreme Soviet declared effective independence from Georgia, although the session was boycotted by ethnic Georgian deputies and the gesture went unrecognised by any other country.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The Abkhaz leadership launched a campaign of ousting Georgian officials from their offices, a process which was accompanied by violence.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] In the meantime, the Abkhaz leader Vladislav Ardzinba intensified his ties with hardline Russian politicians and military elite and declared he was ready for a war with Georgia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] To respond to this situation, Eduard Shevardnadze, new leader of Georgia, interrupted his trip to Western Georgia, where he was touring cities still supporting ousted Gamsakhurdia and was being met by heckling.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Shevardnadze announced that the decision of the Abkhaz faction was "absolutely unexpected" and that it was made without considering the opinion of the majority of population in Abkhazia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] In August 1992, the National Guard of Georgia, led by Tengiz Kitovani entered in Abkhazia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The declared goal was to free Georgian officials held captive in Abkhazia, and to reopen the railway line running through Abkhazia to the rest of Georgia, which was frequently robbed.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] According to Darrell Slider, Abkhaz troops were the first to open fire.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] This led to the beginning of the War in Abkhazia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Abkhaz separatist government retreated to Gudauta where the Russian military base was located.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees reported the ethnic-based violence against Georgians in Gudauta.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The Abkhaz were relatively unarmed at the time and the Georgian troops were able to march into the capital Sukhumi with relatively little resistance and subsequently engaged in ethnically based pillage, looting, assault, and murder.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] They sided with the Abkhaz separatists to fight against the Georgian government.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Russian military did not impede the crossing of the Russia-Georgia border by the North Caucasian militants into Abkhazia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] In the case of Basayev, it has been suggested that when he and the members of his battalion came to Abkhazia, they received training by the Russian Army (though others dispute this), presenting another possible motive.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] On September 25, 1992, Russian Supreme Council (parliament) passed a resolution which condemned Georgia, supported Abkhazia and called for the suspension of the delivery of any weapons and equipment to Georgia and the deployment of a Russian peacekeeping force in Abkhazia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] It was sponsored by a Russian nationalist politician Sergei Baburin, a Russian deputy who met Vladislav Ardzinba and argued that he was not that much sure that Abkhazia was part of Georgia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] In October, the Abkhaz and North Caucasian paramilitaries mounted a major offensive against Gagra after breaking a cease-fire, which drove the Georgian forces out of large swathes of the republic.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Shevardnadze's government accused Russia of giving covert military support to the rebels with the aim of "detaching from Georgia its native territory and the Georgia-Russian frontier land".
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] 1992 ended with the rebels in control of much of Abkhazia northwest of Sukhumi.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The conflict was in stalemate until July 1993, when Abkhaz separatist militias launched an abortive attack on Georgian-held Sukhumi.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] They surrounded and heavily shelled the capital, where Shevardnadze was trapped.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The warring sides agreed to a Russian-brokered truce in Sochi at the end of July.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] But the ceasefire broke down again on 16 September 1993.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Abkhaz forces, with armed support from outside Abkhazia, launched attacks on Sukhumi and Ochamchire.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Notwithstanding UN Security Council's call for the immediate cessation of hostilities and its condemnation of the violation of the ceasefire by the Abkhaz side, fighting continued.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] After ten days of heavy fighting, Sukhumi was taken by Abkhazian forces on 27 September 1993.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Shevardnadze narrowly escaped death, after vowing to stay in the city no matter what.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] He changed his mind, however, and decided to flee when separatist snipers fired on the hotel where he was staying.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Abkhaz, North Caucasian militants, and their allies committed numerous atrocities against the city's remaining ethnic Georgians, in what has been dubbed the Sukhumi Massacre.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The mass killings and destruction continued for two weeks, leaving thousands dead and missing.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The Abkhaz forces quickly overran the rest of Abkhazia as the Georgian government faced a second threat; an uprising by the supporters of the deposed Zviad Gamsakhurdia in the region of Mingrelia (Samegrelo).
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Only a small region of eastern Abkhazia, the upper Kodori gorge, remained under Georgian control (until 2008).
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] During the war, gross human rights violations were reported on both sides.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Georgian troops have been accused of having committed looting and murders "for the purpose of terrorising, robbing and driving the Abkhaz population out of their homes" in the first phase of the war (according to Human Rights Watch).
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) Summits in Budapest (1994), Lisbon (1996) and Istanbul (1999) have recognized the ethnic cleansing of Georgians in Abkhazia in 1992-1993 by the Abkhaz forces and their allies.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] While both sides have committed atrocities, the Abkhaz side has been singled out as responsible for a deliberate displacement campaign "carried out as a military, strategic and political objective in its".
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Before the 1992 War in Abkhazia, Georgians made up nearly half of Abkhazia's population, while less than one-fifth of the population was Abkhaz.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] As the war progressed, confronted with hundreds of thousands of ethnic Georgians who were unwilling to leave their homes, the Abkhaz separatists implemented the process of ethnic cleansing in order to expel and eliminate the Georgian ethnic population in Abkhazia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] About 5,000 were killed, 400 went missing and up to 250,000 ethnic Georgians were expelled from their homes.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] According to International Crisis Group, as of 2006 slightly over 200,000 Georgians remained displaced in Georgia proper.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The campaign of ethnic cleansing also included Russians, Armenians, Greeks, moderate Abkhaz and other minor ethnic groups living in Abkhazia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] More than 20,000 houses owned by ethnic Georgians were destroyed.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Hundreds of schools, kindergartens, churches, hospitals, and historical monuments were pillaged and destroyed.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Following the process of ethnic cleansing and mass expulsion, the population of Abkhazia was reduced from 525,000 in 1989 to 216,000 in 2012.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Pogroms against ethnic Georgians organised by Abkhaz leaders continued even after the end of war, as late as February 1995.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Of about 250,000 Georgian refugees, some 60,000 subsequently returned to Abkhazia's Gali District between 1994 and 1998, but tens of thousands were displaced again when fighting resumed in the Gali District in 1998.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Nevertheless, between 40,000 and 60,000 refugees have returned to the Gali District since 1998, including persons commuting daily across the ceasefire line and those migrating seasonally in accordance with agricultural cycles.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The human rights situation remained precarious for a while in the Georgian-populated areas of the Gali District.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Key officials of the Gali District are virtually all ethnic Abkhaz, though their support staff are ethnic Georgian.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The ethnic Georgians in Gali are deprived of voting rights: during the 2021 local elections, only 900 eligible voters were registered in the Gali district, despite the 30,259 residents in the area.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Presidential elections were held in Abkhazia on 3 October 2004.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Russia supported Raul Khajimba, the prime minister backed by the ailing outgoing separatist President Vladislav Ardzinba.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Posters of Russia's President Vladimir Putin together with Khajimba, who, like Putin, had worked as a KGB official, were everywhere in Sukhumi.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Deputies of Russia's parliament and Russian singers, led by Joseph Cobsohn, a State Duma deputy and a popular singer, came to Abkhazia, campaigning for Khajimba.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] However, Khajimba lost the elections to Sergei Bagapsh.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The tense situation in the republic led to the cancellation of the election results by the Supreme Court.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] After that, a deal was struck between former rivals to run jointly, with Bagapsh as a presidential candidate and Khajimba as a vice-presidential candidate.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] They received more than 90% of the votes in the new election.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] In July 2006, Georgian forces launched a successful police operation against the rebelled administrator of the Georgian-populated Kodori Valley, Emzar Kvitsiani.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Kvitsiani had been appointed by the previous president of Georgia, Eduard Shevardnadze, and refused to recognise the authority of president Mikheil Saakashvili, who succeeded Shevardnadze after the Rose Revolution.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Although Kvitsiani escaped capture by Georgian police, the Kodori Gorge was brought back under the control of the central government in Tbilisi.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Sporadic acts of violence continued throughout the postwar years.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Despite the peacekeeping status of the Russian peacekeepers in Abkhazia, Georgian officials routinely claimed that Russian peacekeepers were inciting violence by supplying Abkhaz rebels with arms and financial support.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Russian support of Abkhazia became pronounced when the Russian ruble became the de facto currency and Russia began issuing passports to the population of Abkhazia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Georgia has also accused Russia of violating its airspace by sending helicopters to attack Georgian-controlled towns in the Kodori Gorge.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] In April 2008, a Russian MiG – prohibited from Georgian airspace, including Abkhazia – shot down a Georgian UAV.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] On 9 August 2008, Abkhazian forces fired on Georgian forces in Kodori Gorge.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] This coincided with the 2008 South Ossetia war where Russia decided to support the Ossetian separatists who had been attacked by Georgia after Russia provoked Georgia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The conflict escalated into a full-scale war between the Russian Federation and the Republic of Georgia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] On 10 August 2008, an estimated 9,000 Russian soldiers entered Abkhazia ostensibly to reinforce the Russian peacekeepers in the republic.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] About 1,000 Abkhazian soldiers moved to expel the residual Georgian forces within Abkhazia in the Upper Kodori Gorge.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] By 12 August the Georgian forces and civilians had evacuated the last part of Abkhazia under Georgian government control.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Russia recognised the independence of Abkhazia on 26 August 2008.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] This was followed by the annulment of the 1994 ceasefire agreement and the termination of UN and OSCE monitoring missions.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] On 28 August 2008, the Parliament of Georgia passed a resolution declaring Abkhazia a Russian-occupied territory.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Since independence was recognised by Russia, a series of controversial agreements were made between the Abkhazian government and the Russian Federation that leased or sold a number of key state assets and relinquished control over the borders.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] In May 2009 several opposition parties and war veteran groups protested against these deals complaining that they undermined state sovereignty and risked "exchanging one colonial power [Georgia] for another [Russia]".
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The vice-president, Raul Khajimba, resigned on 28 May saying he agreed with the criticism the opposition had made.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Subsequently, a conference of opposition parties nominated Raul Khajimba as their candidate in the December 2009 Abkhazian presidential election won by Sergei Bagapsh.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] In the spring of 2014, the opposition submitted an ultimatum to President Aleksandr Ankvab to dismiss the government and make radical reforms.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] On 27 May 2014, in the centre of Sukhumi, 10,000 supporters of the Abkhaz opposition gathered for a mass demonstration.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] On the same day, Ankvab's headquarters in Sukhumi was stormed by opposition groups led by Raul Khajimba, forcing him into flight to Gudauta.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The opposition claimed that the protests were sparked by poverty, but the main point of contention was President Ankvab's liberal policy towards ethnic Georgians in the Gali region.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The opposition said these policies could endanger Abkhazia's ethnic Abkhazian identity.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] After Ankvab fled the capital, on 31 May, the People's Assembly of Abkhazia appointed parliamentary speaker Valery Bganba as acting president, declaring Ankvab unable to serve.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] It also decided to hold an early presidential election on 24 August 2014.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Ankvab soon declared his formal resignation, although he accused his opponents of acting immorally and violating the constitution.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Raul Khajimba was later elected president, taking office in September 2014.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] In November 2014, Vladimir Putin moved to formalise the Abkhazian military's relationship as part of the Russian armed forces, signing a treaty with Khajimba.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The Georgian government denounced the agreement as "a step towards annexation".
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Khajimba was re-elected with a margin of less than 2% in 2019.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] In January 2020 the Abkhazian Supreme Court annulled the results, following protests against Khajimba.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Khajimba resigned the presidency on 12 January, and new elections were called for 22 March.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Aslan Bzhania was elected in the subsequent elections with around 59% of the vote.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Protests took place in November 2024 after the arrest of five opposition activists who opposed an investment agreement with Russia, which led to the resignation of then–President Aslan Bzhania and a new presidential election in February 2025.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Acting president Badra Gunba was elected, receiving 56% of the vote.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Abkhazia covers an area of about 8,665 km2 (3,346 sq mi) at the western end of Georgia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The Caucasus Mountains to the north and northeast separate Abkhazia and the Russian Federation.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] To the east and southeast, Abkhazia is bounded by the Georgian region of Samegrelo-Zemo Svaneti; and on the south and southwest by the Black Sea.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Abkhazia is diverse geographically with lowlands stretching to the extremely mountainous north.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The Greater Caucasus Mountain Range runs along the region's northern border, with its spurs – the Gagra, Bzyb and Kodori ranges – dividing the area into a number of deep, well-watered valleys.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The highest peaks of Abkhazia are in the northeast and east and several exceed 4,000 metres (13,123 ft) above sea level.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Abkhazia's landscape ranges from coastal forests and citrus plantations to permanent snows and glaciers in the north of the region.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Although Abkhazia's complex topographic setting has spared most of the territory from significant human development, its cultivated fertile lands produce tea, tobacco, wine and fruits, a mainstay of the local agricultural sector.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Abkhazia is richly irrigated by small rivers originating in the Caucasus Mountains.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Chief of these are: Kodori, Bzyb, Ghalidzga, and Gumista.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The Psou River separates the region from Russia, and the Inguri serves as a boundary between Abkhazia and Georgia proper.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] There are several periglacial and crater lakes in mountainous Abkhazia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Lake Ritsa is the most important of them.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Because of Abkhazia's proximity to the Black Sea and the shield of the Caucasus Mountains, the region's climate is very mild.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The coastal areas of the republic have a subtropical climate, where the average annual temperature in most regions is around 15 °C (59 °F), and the average January temperature remains above freezing.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The climate at higher elevations varies from maritime mountainous to cold and summerless.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Also, due to its position on the windward slopes of the Caucasus, Abkhazia receives high amounts of precipitation, though humidity decreases further inland.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The mountains of Abkhazia receive significant amounts of snow.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The world's deepest known cave, Veryovkina Cave, is located in Abkhazia's western Caucasus mountains.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The latest survey (as of March 2018) has measured the vertical extent of this cave system as 2,212 metres (7,257 ft) between its highest and lowest explored points.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The lowland regions used to be covered by swaths of oak, beech, and hornbeam, which have since been cleared.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] There are two main entrances into Abkhazia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The southern entrance is at the Inguri bridge, a short distance from the city of Zugdidi.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] The northern entrance ("Psou") is in the town of Leselidze.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] Owing to the situation with a recognition controversy, many foreign governments advise their citizens against travelling to Abkhazia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p01] According to President Raul Khajimba, over the summer of 2015, thousands of tourists visited Abkhazia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Legislative powers are vested in the People's Assembly, which consists of 35 elected members.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The last parliamentary elections were held in March 2022.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Ethnicities other than Abkhaz (Armenians, Russians and Georgians) are claimed to be under-represented in the Assembly.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Most refugees from the 1992–1993 war (mainly ethnic Georgians) have not been able to return and have thus been excluded from the political process.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Some refugees have been allowed to return, in particular in the Gali district where 98% of the population is Georgian as it was before the ethnic cleansing, however, they have been stripped of the voting and other rights.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] As such, during the 2021 local elections, only 900 eligible voters were registered in the Gali district, despite the 30,259 residents in the area.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The territory of the Gali district has also been diminished through addition of some of its lands to Tkvarcheli and Ochamchire districts.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Russia has a major military and economic presence in Abkhazia, and the relationship between the two has been described as asymmetrical, with Abkhazia being heavily dependent on Russia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Abkhazia has adopted Russian technical and commercial standards, and large part of its infrastructure is owned by Russian companies, with Russia heavily investing in the military infrastructure.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The 2014 Treaty on Alliance and Strategic Partnership obliges Abkhazia to coordinate its foreign policy with Russia and merge the armed forces.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] As such, under pressure from Russia, Abkhazia joined Russia in imposing sanctions on Turkey in 2016, becoming Russia's only ally to do so.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Abkhazian officials have stated that they have given the Russian Federation the responsibility of representing their interests abroad.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Some have described Abkhazia as Russia's protectorate with a strong and one-sided dependence.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] According to a 2010 study published by the University of Colorado Boulder, the vast majority of Abkhazia's population supports independence, while a smaller number is in favour of joining the Russian Federation.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Support for reunification with Georgia is very low.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Among ethnic Abkhaz, explicit support for reunification with Georgia is around 1%; a similar figure can be found among ethnic Russians and Armenians as well.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] However, those supporting reunification with Georgia, including ethnic Abkhazians, have faced harassment by the separatist authorities in form of arrests and coercion to apologize publicly.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] In 2014, separatist Republic of Abkhazia and Russian Federation signed the "Treaty of Alliance and Strategic Partnership" with Russia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Based on this treaty, in November 2020, Abkhazia launched a programme on the "formation of common social and economic space" with Russia to make Abkhaz laws and administrative measures more similar to Russian ones in social, economic, health and political spheres.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] On 15 August 2024, the Russian Deputy Minister of Economic Development Dmitry Volvach said that the process of Abkhazia's harmonisation of its laws with Russia was "almost complete".
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The Government of the Autonomous Republic of Abkhazia is the government in exile that Georgia recognises as the legal government of Abkhazia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] This pro-Georgian government maintained a foothold on Abkhazian territory, in the upper Kodori Valley from July 2006 until it was forced out by fighting in August 2008.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] This government is also partly responsible for the affairs of some 250,000 IDPs, forced to leave Abkhazia following the War in Abkhazia and ethnic cleansing that followed.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The current Head of the Government is Giorgi Jincharadze.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] During this period, the Government of Abkhazia in exile, led by Tamaz Nadareishvili, was known for a hard-line stance towards the Abkhaz problem and frequently voiced their opinion that the solution to the conflict can be attained only through Georgia's military response to secessionism.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Later, Nadareishvili's administration was implicated in some internal controversies and had not taken an active part in the politics of Abkhazia until a new chairman, Irakli Alasania, was appointed by President of Georgia, Mikheil Saakashvili, his envoy in the peace talks over Abkhazia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The Republic of Abkhazia is divided into seven raions (districts) named after their primary cities: Gagra, Gudauta, Sukhumi, Ochamchira, Gulripshi, Tkvarcheli and Gali.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] These districts remain mostly unchanged since the break-up of the Soviet Union, with the exception of the Tkvarcheli District, created in 1995 from parts of the Ochamchira and Gali districts.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The President of the Republic appoints districts' heads from those elected to the districts' assemblies.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] There are elected village assemblies whose heads are appointed by the districts' heads.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The administrative subdivisions under Georgian law are identical to the ones outlined above, except for the new Tkvarcheli district.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The Abkhazian Armed Forces are the military of the Republic of Abkhazia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The basis of the Abkhazian armed forces was formed by the ethnically Abkhaz National Guard, which was established in early 1992.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Most of their weapons come from the former Russian airborne division base in Gudauta.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The Abkhazian military is primarily a ground force, but includes small sea and air units.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Russia deploys its own military units as part of the 7th Military Base in Abkhazia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] These units are reportedly subordinate to the Russian 49th Army and include both ground elements and air defence assets.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Abkhazia, Transnistria, and South Ossetia are post-Soviet "frozen conflict" zones.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] These three states maintain friendly relations with each other and form the Community for Democracy and Rights of Nations.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Russia and Nicaragua officially recognised Abkhazia after the Russo-Georgian War.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Venezuela recognised Abkhazia in September 2009.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] In December 2009, Nauru recognised Abkhazia, reportedly in return for $50 million in humanitarian aid from Russia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The unrecognised republic of Transnistria and the partially recognised republic of South Ossetia have recognised Abkhazia since 2006.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Abkhazia is also a member of the Unrepresented Nations and Peoples Organization (UNPO).
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] A majority of sovereign states recognise Abkhazia as an integral part of Georgia and support its territorial integrity according to the principles of international law, although Belarus has expressed sympathy toward the recognition of Abkhazia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Some have officially noted Abkhazia as under occupation by the Russian military.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The United Nations has been urging both sides to settle the dispute through diplomatic dialogue and ratifying the final status of Abkhazia in the Georgian constitution.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] However, the Abkhaz *de facto* government considers Abkhazia a sovereign country even if it is recognised by few other countries.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The Abkhaz side, however, has never accepted the paper as a basis for negotiations.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Eventually, Russia also withdrew its approval of the document.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] In 2005 and 2008, the Georgian government offered Abkhazia a high degree of autonomy and possible federal structure within the borders and jurisdiction of Georgia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] On 18 October 2006, the People's Assembly of Abkhazia passed a resolution, calling upon Russia, international organisations and the rest of the international community to recognise Abkhaz independence on the basis that Abkhazia possesses all the properties of an independent state.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Georgia accuses the Abkhaz secessionists of having conducted a deliberate campaign of ethnic cleansing of up to 250,000 Georgians, a claim supported by the Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe (OSCE; Budapest, Lisbon and Istanbul declaration).
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The UN Security Council has avoided the use of the term "ethnic cleansing" but has affirmed "the unacceptability of the demographic changes resulting from the conflict".
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] On 15 May 2008, the United Nations General Assembly adopted a non-binding resolution recognising the right of all refugees (including victims of reported "ethnic cleansing") to return to Abkhazia and to retain or regain their property rights there.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] On 3 July 2008, the OSCE Parliamentary Assembly passed a resolution at its annual session in Astana, expressing concern over Russia's recent moves in breakaway Abkhazia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] On 9 July 2012, the OSCE Parliamentary Assembly passed a resolution at its annual session in Monaco, underlining Georgia's territorial integrity and referring to breakaway Abkhazia and South Ossetia as "occupied territories".
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] In late October 2008, President Saakashvili signed into law legislation on the occupied territories passed by the Georgian Parliament.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The law covers the breakaway regions of Abkhazia and Tskhinvali (territories of the former South Ossetian Autonomous Oblast).
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The law spells out restrictions on free movement and economic activity in the territories.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] In particular, according to the law, foreign citizens should enter the two breakaway regions only through Georgia proper.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Entry into Abkhazia should be carried out from the Zugdidi Municipality, and into South Ossetia from the Gori Municipality.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The major road leading to South Ossetia from the rest of Georgia passes through the Gori District.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The legislation, however, also lists "special" cases in which entry into the breakaway regions will not be regarded as illegal.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] It also bans air, sea, and railway communications and international transit via the regions, mineral exploration, and money transfers.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The provision covering economic activities is retroactive, going back to 1990.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The law says that the Russian Federation – the state that has carried out military occupation – is fully responsible for the violation of human rights in Abkhazia and South Ossetia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The Russian Federation, according to the document, is also responsible for compensation of material and moral damage inflicted on Georgian citizens, stateless persons, and foreign citizens, who are in Georgia and enter the occupied territories with appropriate permits.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The law also says that de facto state agencies and officials operating in the occupied territories are regarded by Georgia as illegal.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The law will remain in force until "the full restoration of Georgian jurisdiction" over the breakaway regions is realised.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] According to a 2006 report, Georgia considers all residents of Abkhazia its citizens, while they see themselves as Abkhaz citizens.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] In the summer of 2011, the Parliament of Georgia adopted a package of legislative amendments providing for the issuance of neutral identification and travel documents to residents of Abkhazia and the former South Ossetian autonomous province of Georgia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The document allows travelling abroad as well as enjoying the social benefits existing in Georgia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The new neutral identification and travel documents were called "neutral passports".
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The status-neutral passports do not carry the state symbols of Georgia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Abkhazia's foreign minister, Viacheslav Chirikba, criticised the status-neutral passports and called their introduction "unacceptable".
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Some Abkhazian residents with Russian passports were being denied Schengen visas.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] As of May 2013, neutral documents have been recognised by Japan, the Czech Republic, Latvia, Lithuania, Slovakia, the United States, Bulgaria, Poland, Israel, Estonia, and Romania.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] During the Georgian–Abkhaz conflict, the Russian authorities and military supplied logistical and military aid to the separatist side.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Today, Russia still maintains a strong political and military influence over separatist rule in Abkhazia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Russia has also issued passports to the citizens of Abkhazia since 2000 (as Abkhazian passports cannot be used for international travel) and subsequently paid them retirement pensions and other monetary benefits.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] More than 80% of the Abkhazian population had received Russian passports by 2006.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] As Russian citizens living abroad, Abkhazians do not pay Russian taxes or serve in the Russian Army.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] About 53,000 Abkhazian passports have been issued as of May 2007.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Moscow, at certain times, hinted that it might recognise Abkhazia and South Ossetia when Western countries recognised the independence of Kosovo, suggesting that they had created a precedent.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Later in April 2008, Russia accused Georgia of trying to exploit NATO support in order to control Abkhazia by force and announced it would increase its military presence in the region, pledging to retaliate militarily against Georgia's efforts.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Georgian Prime Minister Lado Gurgenidze said Georgia will treat any additional troops in Abkhazia as "aggressors".
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] In response to the Russo-Georgian War, the Federal Assembly of Russia called an extraordinary session on 25 August 2008 to discuss the recognition of Abkhazia and South Ossetia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Following a unanimous resolution passed by both houses of the parliament calling on the Russian president to recognise the independence of the breakaway republics, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev officially recognised both on 26 August 2008.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Russian recognition was condemned by NATO member states, OSCE, and European Council members due to "violation of territorial integrity and international law".
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon stated that sovereign states have to decide for themselves whether they want to recognise the independence of disputed regions.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Russia has begun work on the establishment of a naval base in Ochamchire by dredging the coast to allow the passage of its larger naval vessels.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] As a response to the Georgian sea blockade of Abkhazia, in which the Georgian coast guard had been detaining ships heading to and from Abkhazia, Russia warned Georgia against ship seizures and said that a unit of Russian guard boats would provide security for ships bound for Abkhazia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The extent of Russian influence in Abkhazia has caused some locals to say that Abkhazia is under full Russian control, but they still prefer Russian influence over Georgian.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The UN's position has been that there will be no forcible change of international borders.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Any settlement must be freely negotiated and based on autonomy for Abkhazia, legitimised by referendum under international observation once the multi-ethnic population has returned.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The OSCE has increasingly engaged in dialogue with officials and civil society representatives in Abkhazia, especially from non-governmental organisations (NGOs) and the media, regarding human standards in the region, and is considering a presence in Gali.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The OSCE expressed concern and condemnation over the ethnic cleansing of Georgians in Abkhazia during the 1994 Budapest Summit decision and later at the Lisbon Summit Declaration in 1996.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The US rejects the unilateral secession of Abkhazia and urges its integration into Georgia as an autonomous unit.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] In 1998, the US announced its readiness to allocate up to $15 million for the rehabilitation of infrastructure in the Gali region if substantial progress is made in the peace process.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] USAID has already funded some humanitarian initiatives for Abkhazia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] On 5 October 2006, Javier Solana, the High Representative for the Common Foreign and Security Policy of the European Union, ruled out the possibility of replacing the Russian peacekeepers with the EU force.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] On 13 October 2006, the UN Security Council unanimously adopted a resolution, based on a Group of Friends of the Secretary-General draft, extending the UNOMIG mission until 15 April 2007.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Acknowledging that the "new and tense situation" resulted, at least in part, from the Georgian special forces' operation in the upper Kodori Valley, the resolution urged the country to ensure that no troops unauthorised by the Moscow ceasefire agreement were present in that area.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] It urged the leadership of the Abkhaz side to address seriously the need for a dignified, secure return of refugees and internally displaced persons and to reassure the local population in the Gali district that their residency rights and identity would be respected.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Calling on both parties to follow up on dialogue initiatives, it further urged them to comply fully with all previous agreements regarding non-violence and confidence-building, in particular those concerning the separation of forces.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Regarding the disputed role of the peacekeepers from the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS), the Council stressed the importance of close, effective cooperation between UNOMIG and that force and looked to all sides to continue to extend the necessary cooperation to them.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The HALO Trust, an international non-profit organisation that specialises in the removal of the debris of war, has been active in Abkhazia since 1999 and has completed the removal of landmines in Sukhumi and Gali districts.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] It declared Abkhazia "mine-free" in 2011.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] France-based international NGO Première-Urgence has been implementing a food security programme to support the vulnerable populations affected by the frozen conflict for almost 10 years.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Russia does not allow the European Union Monitoring Mission in Georgia (EUMM) to enter Abkhazia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Abkhazia has been recognised as an independent state by only five states: Russia, Venezuela, Nicaragua, Nauru, and Syria.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Georgia and other countries consider Abkhazia as Georgia's sovereign territory.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Russia was the first country to officially recognise Abkhazia, which it did after the 2008 Russo-Georgian War.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] After the Russian recognition, Nicaragua, Venezuela, Nauru, Vanuatu, and Tuvalu soon followed suit and recognised Abkhazia and South Ossetia as independent states.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] However, in 2013 and 2014, Vanuatu and Tuvalu scrapped their recognition.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Russia invested a significant amount of money in a diplomatic strategy to promote the recognition of Abkhazia and South Ossetia and display its soft power.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] However, Russia appeared to have stopped investing in the recognition project after 2014.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] One possible reason could be the worsening of Russia's financial situation following the start of the Russo-Ukrainian war in 2014 and the subsequent imposition of international sanctions on Russia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Consequently, Abkhazia launched its own campaign to strengthen its diplomatic relations with foreign countries and present itself as an independent actor.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] As a part of these efforts, Abkhaz officials paid official visits to numerous countries, including China, Italy, Turkey, and Israel.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Additionally, they held high-level meetings with political representatives from South Africa, Jordan, and El Salvador, and sent diplomatic notes to different countries, including Egypt, France, Guatemala, and Sri Lanka.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] This campaign reached its peak in 2017, but subsequently decreased and largely halted with the beginning of the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] It was largely unsuccessful and ended in failure as Syria remains the only country that has recognised Abkhazia and South Ossetia since 2009.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] One of the early proposals was voiced before the war, in March 1989, when the Abkhaz ethno-nationalist organisation Aidgylara issued the Lykhny Appeal, calling for Abkhazia to become part of the Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] This is thought to be a starting point for the Abkhazia conflict between the separatists and local Georgian population in Abkhazia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] After the war, on 18 November 1993, a month after its ending and ethnic cleansing of Georgians in Abkhazia, the leader of Abkhazia Vladislav Ardzinba proposed to hold a referendum to join the Russian Federation.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] In 2001, a similar desire was voiced by Abkhazia's Prime Minister Anri Jergenia, who said that Abkhazia was preparing to join Russia and that it was going to hold a referendum on that issue.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] In October 2022, in an interview to the Russian TV, President of Abkhazia Aslan Bzhania declared Abkhazia's readiness to host a Russian navy and join the Russia-Belarus Union State.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] However, the proposal has been criticised as impractical since Belarus does not recognise Abkhazia as a sovereign state and considers it to be part of Georgia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] In August 2023, Deputy Chair of Russian Security Council Dmitry Medvedev also voiced support for these proposals, accusing Georgia of "escalating tensions" by its potential membership to the NATO, and saying that there were "good reasons" for Abkhazia and South Ossetia to join Russia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Medvedev also mocked Georgia's desire to restore its territorial integrity, saying that "Georgia can only be united as part of Russia".
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Georgia criticised the proposals for Abkhazia's entry into the Russian Federation and Union State.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] In 2014, Georgia's Foreign Ministry issued a statement, calling the Russia-Abkhazia treaty on integration a *de facto* annexation.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The economy of Abkhazia is integrated with Russia as outlined in a bilateral agreement published in November 2014.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The country uses the Russian ruble as its currency, and the two countries share a common economic and customs union.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Abkhazia has experienced a modest economic upswing since the 2008 South Ossetia war and Russia's subsequent recognition of Abkhazia's independence.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] About half of Abkhazia's state budget is financed with aid money from Russia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Tourism is a key industry and, according to Abkhazia's authorities, almost a million tourists (mainly from Russia) came to Abkhazia in 2007.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Abkhazia exports wine and fruits, especially tangerines and hazelnuts.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Electricity is largely supplied by the Inguri hydroelectric power station located on the Inguri River between Abkhazia and Georgia (proper) and operated jointly by both parties.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] In the first half of 2012, the principal trading partners of Abkhazia were Russia (64%) and Turkey (18%).
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Russia also called on other CIS members to undertake similar steps, but met with protests from Tbilisi and lack of support from the other CIS countries.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Despite the controversial status of the territory and its damaged infrastructure, tourism in Abkhazia grew following the Russian recognition of Abkhazian independence in 2008 due to the arrival of Russian tourists.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] In 2009 the number of Russian tourists in Abkhazia increased by 20% and the total number of Russian tourists reached 1 million.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] After the tourist boom many Russian businesses began to invest money in Abkhazian tourist infrastructure.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] With the main highway of the country being rebuilt in 2014 many damaged hotels in Gagra are either being restored or demolished.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] In 2014, 1.16 million Russian tourists visited Abkhazia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] According to the last census in 2011 Abkhazia had 240,705 inhabitants.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The Department of Statistics of Georgia estimated Abkhazia's population to be approximately 179,000 in 2003, and 178,000 in 2005 (the last year when such estimates were published in Georgia).
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] *Encyclopædia Britannica* estimates the population in 2007 at 180,000 and the International Crisis Group estimated Abkhazia's total population in 2006 to be between 157,000 and 190,000 (or between 180,000 and 220,000 as estimated by UNDP in 1998).
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The ethnic composition of Abkhazia has played a central role in the Georgian-Abkhazian conflict.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The 1992–1993 war with Georgia resulted in the expulsion and flight of over half of the republic's population, which had numbered 525,061 in the 1989 census.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The population of Abkhazia remains ethnically very diverse, even after the 1992–1993 war.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] At present the population of Abkhazia is mainly made up of ethnic Abkhaz (50.7% according to the 2011 census), Russians, Armenians, Georgians (mostly Mingrelians, but also Svans), and Greeks.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Other ethnicities include Ukrainians, Belarusians, Ossetians, Tatars, Turks, Roma and Estonians.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Greeks constituted a significant minority in the area in the early 1920s (50,000), and remained a major ethnic group until 1945, when they were deported to Central Asia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Under the Soviet Union, the Russian, Armenian, and Georgian populations grew faster than the Abkhaz population, due to large-scale enforced migration, especially under the rule of Joseph Stalin and Lavrenty Beria.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] At the time of the 1989 census, Abkhazia's Georgian population numbered 239,872, forming around 45.7% of the population, and the Armenian population was 77,000.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Due to ethnic cleansing and displacement due to people fleeing the 1992–1993 war, the Georgian population, and to a lesser extent the Russian and Armenian populations, has greatly declined.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] In 2003 Armenians formed the second-largest minority group in Abkhazia (closely matching the Georgians), numbering 44,869.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] By the time of the 2011 census, Georgians formed the second-largest minority group with a population of 46,455.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Despite the official numbers, unofficial sources estimate that the Abkhaz and Armenian communities are roughly equal in number.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] In the wake of the Syrian civil war, Abkhazia granted refugee status to a few hundred Syrians with Abkhaz, Abazin and Circassian ancestry.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Facing a growing Armenian community, this move has been linked with the wish of the ruling Abkhaz —who have often been in the minority on their territory— to tilt the demographic balance in favour of the titular nation.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Thousands of Abkhaz, known as *muhajirun*, were exiled to the Ottoman Empire in the mid-19th century after resisting the Russian conquest of the Caucasus.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Today, Turkey is home to the world's largest Abkhaz diaspora community.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Size estimates vary – diaspora leaders say 1 million people; Abkhaz estimates range from 150,000 to 500,000.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The languages spoken in Abkhazia are Abkhaz, Russian, the Kartvelian languages Mingrelian and Svan, Armenian, and Greek.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The Autonomous Republic passed a law in 2007 defining the Abkhaz language as the only state language of Abkhazia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] As such, Abkhaz is the required language for legislative and executive council debates (with translation from and to Russian) and at least half of the text of all magazines and newspapers must be in Abkhaz.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Despite the official status of Abkhaz, the dominance of other languages within Abkhazia, especially Russian, is so great that experts called it an "endangered language" in 2004.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] During the Soviet era, language instruction would begin in schools in Abkhaz, only to switch to Russian for the majority of required schooling.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The government of the Republic is attempting to institute Abkhaz-only primary education but there has been limited success due to a lack of facilities and educational materials.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The primary schools in Kartvelian-speaking areas switched from Georgian to Russian in 2016.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] A majority of inhabitants of Abkhazia are Christian (Eastern Orthodox (see also: Abkhazian Orthodox Church) and Armenian Apostolic) while a significant minority are Sunni Muslim.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The Abkhaz Native Religion has undergone a strong revival in recent decades.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] There is a very small number of adherents of Judaism, Jehovah's Witnesses and new religious movements.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The Jehovah's Witnesses organisation has officially been banned since 1995, though the decree is not currently enforced.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] According to the constitution of Abkhazia, the adherents of all religions have equal rights before the law.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] According to a survey held in 2003, 60% of respondents identified themselves as Christian, 16% as Muslim, 8% as atheist or irreligious, 8% as adhering to the traditional Abkhazian religion or as Pagan, 2% as follower of other religions and 6% as undecided.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] After the break-up of the Soviet Union, many Abkhazians kept their Soviet passports, even after a decade, and used them to eventually apply for Russian citizenship.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Before 2002, Russian law allowed residents of former Soviet Union to apply for citizenship if they had not become citizens of their newly independent states.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The new citizenship law of Russia adopted on 31 May 2002 introduced a simplified procedure of citizenship acquisition for former citizens of the Soviet Union regardless of their place of residence.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] In Abkhazia and South Ossetia, the application process was simplified even further, and people could apply even without leaving their homes.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Russian non-governmental organisations with close ties to Russian officialdom simply took their papers to a nearby Russian city for processing.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Abkhazians began mass acquisition of Russian passports in 2002.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] It is reported that the public organisation the Congress of Russian Communities of Abkhazia started collecting Abkhazians' Soviet-era travel documents.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] It then sent them to a consular department specially set up by Russian Foreign Ministry officials in the city of Sochi.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] After they were checked, Abkhazian applicants were granted Russian citizenship.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] By 25 June 2002, an estimated 150,000 people in Abkhazia had acquired the new passports, joining 50,000 who already possessed Russian citizenship.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The Sukhum authorities, although officially not involved in the registration for Russian nationality process, openly encouraged it.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Government officials said privately that President Putin's administration agreed with the passport acquisition during Abkhazia's prime minister Djergenia's visit to Moscow in May 2002.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] When the *"passportisation"* policy was launched in 2002, even Russia recognised Abkhazia as part of Georgia at that time.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Russia's extraterritorial naturalisation practice in South Ossetia and Abkhazia constituted an intervention contrary to international law and it violated Georgia's territorial sovereignty.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The passportisation caused outrage in Tbilisi, worsening its already shaky relations with Russia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The Georgian Foreign Ministry issued a statement insisting that Abkhazians were citizens of Georgia and calling the passport allocation an "unprecedented illegal campaign".
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] President Eduard Shevardnadze said that he would be asking his Russian counterpart, Vladimir Putin, for an explanation.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The speaker of parliament Nino Burjanadze said that she would raise the matter at the forthcoming OSCE parliamentary assembly.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] 1 February 2011 was the last day in the post-Soviet era when a passport of USSR was valid for crossing the Russian-Abkhaz border.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] According to the staff of Abkhazia's passport and visa service, there were about two to three thousand mostly elderly people left with Soviet passports who had no chance of acquiring new documents.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] These people were not able to get Russian citizenship.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] But they can first get an internal Abkhaz passport and then a travelling passport to visit Russia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] In 2005, citing the need to integrate ethnic Georgian residents of eastern districts of Abkhazia, the then leadership of Abkhazia showed signs of a softening stance towards granting of citizenship to the residents of Gali, Ochamchire and Tkvarcheli districts.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] According to the Abkhazian law on citizenship, ethnic Abkhazians, regardless of place of residence, can become Abkhaz citizens.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Those who are not ethnic Abkhazians are eligible for citizenship if they lived in Abkhazia for at least five years prior to the adoption of the act of independence in October 1999.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] This provision aimed at creating a legal hurdle in obtaining Abkhaz passports for those ethnic Georgians who fled Abkhazia as a result of 1992–1993 armed conflict and who then returned to the Gali district.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Abkhazian legislation forbids citizens of Abkhazia from holding dual citizenship with any other state apart from Russia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Ethnic Georgians who have returned to the Gali district and want to obtain Abkhaz passports, according to Abkhazian law, should undergo lengthy procedures which also include a requirement to submit documented proof that they renounced their Georgian citizenship.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] So in his official speeches, Bagapsh often added the Gali Georgians to population estimates of the Abkhaz, disregarding the fact that they still thought of themselves as ethnic Georgians rather than Abkhaz.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] In early 2013 the process of passportisation of ethnic Georgians came under the scrutiny of Abkhaz opposition groups who turned this issue into one of the central topics of the breakaway region's internal politics, and issuing of passports was suspended in May.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Pressures have been placed upon teachers in areas of Abkhazia which retain large Georgian populations to abandon the use of the Georgian language in education and adopt Russian textbooks.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] According to the Abkhaz officials, more than 26,000 passports were distributed in Gali, Tkvarcheli and Ochamchire districts, including about 23,000 of which were given out since Russian recognition of Abkhazia's independence in August 2008.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] These political debates have caused concerns in the ethnic Georgian population of Abkhazia, who reside mainly in Gali district, that they would be stripped of Abkhazian citizenship and thus forced to leave Abkhazia again.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] In October 2013 Alexander Ankvab signed a document ordering the firing of Stanislav Lakoba.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The document did not state any reason for the decision but Lakoba saw it as related to his political position on granting citizenship to Georgians living in Gali.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Lakoba claimed that, according to data from the Abkhaz Security Council, 129 local people in Gali fought against Abkhazia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Local political parties and the coordination council of civil organisations expressed concern about Lakoba's dismissal.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] They claimed that, by dismissing him, the president "made an illegal process legal" – giving Abkhazian passports to Georgian citizens.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Until the 19th century, young people from Abkhazia usually received their education mainly at religious schools (Muslims at madrasas and Christians at seminaries), although a small number of children from wealthy families had opportunity to travel to foreign countries for education.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The first modern educational institutions (both schools and colleges) in Abkhazia were established in the late 19th-early 20th centuries and rapidly grew until the second half of the 20th century.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] By the middle of the 20th century, Sukhumi had become a home for large educational institutions (both higher education institutions and technical vocational education and training (TVET) colleges) and largest students' community in Abkhazia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] According to the official statistical data, Abkhazia has 12 TVET colleges (as of 2019, est.) providing education and vocational training to youth mostly in the capital city, though there are several colleges in all major district centres.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Independent international assessments suggest that these colleges train in about 20 different specialties attracting between 1000 and 1300 young people annually (aged between 16 and 29) (as of 2019, est.).
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The apsuara, the Abkhaz code of honour, is very stringent regarding hospitality.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] One of its principles is to respect guests even if they have committed crimes against the host.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The written Abkhaz literature appeared relatively recently, in the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] However, Abkhaz share the Nart sagas, a series of tales about mythical heroes, with other Caucasian peoples.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The Abkhaz alphabet was created in the 19th century.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The first newspaper in Abkhaz, called *Abkhazia* and edited by Dmitry Gulia, appeared in 1917.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Arguably the most famous Abkhaz writers are Fazil Iskander, who wrote mostly in Russian, and Bagrat Shinkuba, a poet and writer.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Football remains the most popular sport in Abkhazia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Other popular sports include basketball, boxing and wrestling.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] The National Basketball Team of Abkhazia played its first game with the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus Basketball team on 27 May 2015, which Abkhaz team won by 76–59.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Abkhaz basketball team "Apsny" also plays in the Russian Basketball League's Third-Tier in Krasnodar Krai.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Abkhazia has had its own amateur football league called the Abkhazian Premier League, but it has no international football union membership.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] In total, there are nineteen Abkhazian Football Clubs across the two leagues.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] In 2016 it hosted and won the ConIFA World Football Cup.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Since the early 2000s, tennis has become increasingly popular among school age children in Abkhazia.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] Several tennis players from Sukhumi participated as the national competitions in Russia and played at major international competitions under the Russian flag.
[src:brittany/abkhazia-p02] For example, tennis player Alen Avidzba participated at the Davis Cup in 2016 and Amina Anshba won a silver medal at an international tournament in Turkey in 2017.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Brittany has also been referred to as **Little Britain** (as opposed to Great Britain, with which it shares an etymology).
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] It is bordered by the English Channel to the north, Normandy to the northeast, eastern Pays de la Loire to the southeast, the Bay of Biscay to the south, and the Celtic Sea and the Atlantic Ocean to the west.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Brittany is the site of some of the world's oldest standing architecture, home to the Cairn of Barnenez, the Tumulus Saint-Michel and others, which date to the early 5th millennium BC.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The historical province of Brittany is split among five French departments: Finistère in the west, Côtes-d'Armor in the north, Ille-et-Vilaine in the northeast, Morbihan in the south and Loire-Atlantique in the southeast.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Loire-Atlantique now belongs to the Pays de la Loire region while the other four departments make up the Brittany region.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] At the 2010 census, the population of historic Brittany was estimated to be 4,475,295.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] In 2017, the largest metropolitan areas were Nantes (934,165 inhabitants), Rennes (733,320 inhabitants), and Brest (321,364 inhabitants).
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] A nationalist movement seeks greater autonomy within the French Republic, or independence from it.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The reunification of Brittany is supported by half of the inhabitants of Brittany and of Loire-Atlantique, and is considered a prerequisite to further autonomy.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The word *Brittany*, along with its French, Breton and Gallo equivalents *Bretagne*, *Breizh* and *Bertaèyn*, derive from the Latin *Britannia*, which means 'land of the Britons'.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] This word had been used by the Romans since the 1st century to refer to Great Britain, and more specifically the Roman province of Britain.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] This word derives from a Greek word Πρεττανική, *Prettanikḗ* or Βρεττανίαι, *Brettaníai*, used by Pytheas, an explorer from Massalia who visited the British Isles around 320 BC.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The Greek word itself comes from the common Brythonic ethnonym reconstructed as **Pritanī*, itself from Proto-Celtic **kʷritanoi* (ultimately from Proto-Indo-European **kʷer-* 'to cut, make').
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] In Roman times, *Armorica* included what is now Brittany.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] This was an indefinite region that extended along the English Channel coast from the Seine estuary, then along the Atlantic coast to the Loire estuary and, according to several sources, maybe to the Garonne estuary.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] This term probably comes from a Gallic word, *aremorica*, which means 'close to the sea'.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Another name, *Letauia* (in English "Litavis"), was used until the 12th century.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] It possibly means 'wide and flat' or 'to expand' and it gave the Welsh name for Brittany, *Llydaw*.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] After the fall of the Western Roman Empire, many Cornish Britons settled in western Armorica to escape the Saxons and the region started to be called *Britannia*, although this name only replaced *Armorica* in the sixth century or perhaps by the end of the fifth.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Breton-speaking people may pronounce the word *Breizh* in two different ways, according to their region of origin.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Breton can be divided into two main dialects: the *KLT* (Kerne-Leon-Trégor) and the dialect of the Vannetais.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] KLT speakers pronounce it [brɛjs] and would write it *Breiz*, while the Vannetais speakers pronounce it [brɛχ] and would write it *Breih*.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The official spelling *Breizh* is a compromise between both variants.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] In 1941, efforts to unify the dialects led to the creation of the so-called *Breton zh*, a standard which has never been widely accepted.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Gallo, on the other hand, has never had a widely accepted orthography, and several coexist.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] For instance, the name of the region in that language can be written *Bertaèyn* in *ELG* orthography, or *Bertègn* in *MOGA*, and a couple of other orthographies also exist.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Brittany has been inhabited by humans since the Lower Palaeolithic.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] This population was scarce and very similar to the other Neanderthals found in the whole of Western Europe.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Their only original feature was a distinct culture, called the "Colombanian".
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] One of the oldest hearths in the world has been found in Plouhinec, Finistère.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Homo sapiens settled in Brittany around 35,000 years ago.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] They replaced or absorbed the Neanderthals and developed local industries, similar to the Châtelperronian or to the Magdalenian.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] After the last glacial period, the warmer climate allowed the area to become heavily wooded.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] At that time, Brittany was populated by relatively large communities who started to change their lifestyles from a life of hunting and gathering, to become settled farmers.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Agriculture was introduced during the 5th millennium BC by migrants from the south and east.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] However, the Neolithic Revolution in Brittany did not happen due to a radical change of population, but by slow immigration and exchange of skills.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Neolithic Brittany is characterised by important megalithic production and sites such as Quelfénnec, it is sometimes designated as the "core area" of megalithic culture.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The oldest monuments, cairns, were followed by princely tombs and stone rows.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The Morbihan *département*, on the southern coast, comprises a large share of these structures, including the Carnac stones and the Broken Menhir of Er Grah in the Locmariaquer megaliths, the largest single stone erected by Neolithic people.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Those people had strong economic ties to the Insular Celts, especially for the tin trade.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Several tribes also belonged to an "Armorican confederation" which, according to Julius Caesar, gathered the Curiosolitae, the Redones, the Osismii, the Unelli, the Caletes, the Lemovices and the Ambibarii.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The Unelli, Caletes, and Lemovices were respectively located in Cotentin (Lower-Normandy), pays de Caux (Upper-Normandy), and Limousin (Aquitaine); the location of the Ambibarii is unknown.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The Caletes are sometimes also considered Belgians, and *Lemovices* is probably a mistake for *Lexovii* (Lower-Normandy).
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] During the Gallic Wars, the Veneti were defeated in the Battle of Morbihan off the coast of Brittany.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] At the conclusion of the Gallic Wars, the region became part of the Roman Republic in 51 BC.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] It was included in the province of Gallia Lugdunensis in 13 BC.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Gallic towns and villages were redeveloped according to Roman standards, and several cities were created.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] These cities are Condate (Rennes), Vorgium (Carhaix), Darioritum (Vannes) and Condevincum or Condevicnum (Nantes).
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Together with Fanum Martis (Corseul), they were the capitals of the local civitates.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] They all had a grid plan and a forum, and sometimes a temple, a basilica, thermae or an aqueduct, like Carhaix.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The Romans also built three major roads through the region.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] However, most of the population remained rural.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The free peasants lived in small huts, whereas the landowners and their employees lived in proper villae rusticae.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The Gallic deities continued to be worshipped, and were often assimilated to the Roman gods.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Only a small number of statues depicting Roman gods were found in Brittany, and most of the time they combine Celtic elements.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] During the 3rd century AD, the region was attacked several times by Franks, Alamanni and pirates.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] At the same time, the local economy collapsed and many farming estates were abandoned.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] To face the invasions, many towns and cities were fortified, like Nantes, Rennes and Vannes.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] This area was also affected by the Bagaudae (also spelled bacaudae) during this period, which were groups of peasant insurgents.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The Bagaudae achieved some temporary and scattered successes under the leadership of peasants as well as former members of local ruling elites.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Toward the end of the 4th century, the Britons of Domnonée (modern Devon and Cornwall) on the South-Western peninsula of Great Britain began to emigrate to Armorica, which is why the Breton language is more closely related to recorded Cornish.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The history behind such an establishment is unclear, but medieval Breton, Angevin and Welsh sources connect it to a figure known as Conan Meriadoc.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Welsh literary sources assert that Conan came to Armorica on the orders of the Roman usurper Magnus Maximus, who sent some of his British troops to Gaul to enforce his claims and settled them in Armorica.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] This account was supported by the Counts of Anjou, who claimed descent from a Roman soldier expelled from Lower Brittany by Conan on Magnus's orders.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The army recruited for Flavius Aetius to combat Attila the Hun at the Battle of the Catalaunian Plains included Romans, Visigoths, Franks, Alans and Armoricans, amongst others.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The Alans were placed front and centre, opposite the Huns.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The Armoricans supplied archers who attacked the Huns' front lines during the main battle and thwarted Attila's night assault on the Roman camp with a hail of arrows "like rain".
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] After the battle was won, Aetius sent the Alans to Armorica and Galicia.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The late 5th century Brittonic leader Riothamus received correspondence from the eminent Roman jurist Sidonius Apollinaris and was called "King of the Britons" by Jordanes.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Some suggest that he was a Breton, though others believe that he was from Britain, pointing to the passage that he arrived in the land of the Biturges "by way of Ocean", which would hardly have been efficient or required for a Breton.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Both historians describe Riothamus's losing battle against King Euric of the Visigoths at Déols around the year 470.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] In response to a plea from the Roman Emperor Anthemius, Riothamus had led twelve thousand men to establish a military presence in Bourges in central Gaul, but was betrayed by Arvandus, the Praetorian Prefect of Gaul, and subsequently ambushed by Euric's army.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] After a long battle, the Armorican survivors escaped to Avallon in Burgundy, after which they are lost to history.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] According to Breton king-lists, Riotham survived and reigned as Prince of Domnonia until his death sometime between 500 and 520, though this may have been a different person.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Brythonic (British Celtic) settlement increased during the Anglo-Saxon invasion of Britain in the 5th and 6th centuries to seek refuge from the Anglo-Saxon invaders.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] It is from this event that Brittany derives its name.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Scholars such as Léon Fleuriot have suggested a two-wave model of migration from Britain which saw the emergence of an independent Breton people and established the dominance of the Brythonic Breton language in Armorica.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Their petty kingdoms are now known by the names of the counties that succeeded them—Domnonée (Devon), Cornouaille (Cornwall), Léon (Caerleon); but these names in Breton and Latin are in most cases identical to their British homelands.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] At the beginning of the medieval era, Brittany was divided among three kingdoms, Domnonea, Cornouaille and Broërec.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] These realms eventually merged into a single state during the 9th century.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The unification of Brittany was carried out by Nominoe, king between 845 and 851 and considered as the Breton *Pater Patriae*.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Among the immigrant Britons, there were some clergymen who helped the evangelisation of the region, which was still pagan, particularly in rural areas.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] His son Erispoe secured the independence of the new kingdom of Brittany and won the Battle of Jengland against Charles the Bald.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The Bretons won another war in 867, and the kingdom reached then its maximum extent: It received parts of Normandy, Maine and Anjou and the Channel Islands.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Brittany was heavily attacked by the Vikings at the beginning of the 10th century.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The kingdom lost its eastern territories, including Normandy and Anjou, and the county of Nantes was given to Fulk I of Anjou in 909.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Nantes was seized by the Vikings in 914.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] At this time Brittany was also called Lydwiccum.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Nantes was eventually liberated by Alan II of Brittany in 937 with the support of his godbrother King Æthelstan of England.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Alan II totally expelled the Vikings from Brittany and recreated a strong Breton state.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] For aiding in removing the problem, Alan paid homage to Louis IV of France (who was Æthelstan's nephew and had returned from England in the same year as Alan II) and thus Brittany ceased to be a kingdom and became a duchy.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Several Breton lords helped William the Conqueror to invade England and the Bretons formed over a third of the landing force in 1066.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] William's double-second cousin Alan Rufus and the latter's brother Brian of Brittany).
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The Bretons helped to liberate the Cornish, replacing Anglo-Saxon land owners.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Some of these lords were powerful rivals.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Medieval Brittany was far from being a united nation.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The French king maintained envoys in Brittany, alliances contracted by local lords often overlapped and there was no specific Breton unity.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] For example, Brittany replaced Latin with French as its official language in the 13th century, 300 years before France did so, and the Breton language did not have formal status.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The foreign policy of the Duchy changed many times; the Dukes were usually independent, but they often contracted alliances with England or France depending on who was threatening them at that point.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Their support for each nation became very important during the 14th century because the English kings had started to claim the French throne.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The Breton War of Succession, a local episode of the Hundred Years' War, saw the House of Blois, backed by the French, fighting with the House of Montfort, backed by the English.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The Montforts won in 1364 and enjoyed a period of total independence until the end of the Hundred Years' War, because France was weakened and stopped sending royal envoys to the Court of Brittany.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Brittany importantly lost the Mad War against France in 1488, mostly because of its internal divisions that were exacerbated by the corruption at the court of Francis II, Duke of Brittany.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Indeed, some rebel Breton lords were fighting on the French side.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] As a result of the Mad War, the Duke Francis II could not have his daughter Anne married without the king of France's consent.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Nonetheless, she married the Holy Roman Emperor in 1490, leading to a crisis with France.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Charles VIII of France besieged Rennes and had the marriage cancelled.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] After he died childless, Anne had to marry his heir and cousin Louis XII.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Anne unsuccessfully tried to preserve Breton independence, but she died in 1514, and the union between the two crowns was formally carried out by Francis I in 1532.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] He granted several privileges to Brittany, such as exemption from the gabelle, a tax on salt that was very unpopular in France.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Under the Ancien Régime, Brittany and France were governed as separate countries but under the same crown, so Breton aristocrats in the French royal court were classed as *Princes étrangers* (foreign princes).
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] From the 15th to the 18th century, Brittany reached an economic golden age.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The region was located on the seaways near Spain, England and the Dutch Republic and it greatly benefited from the creation of the French colonial empire.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Local seaports like Brest and Saint-Brieuc quickly expanded, and Lorient, first spelt "L'Orient", was founded in the 17th century.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Saint-Malo was then known for its corsairs, Brest was a major base for the French Navy and Nantes flourished with the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] On its side, the inland provided hemp ropes and canvas and linen sheets.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] However, Colbertism, which encouraged the creation of many factories, did not favour the Breton industry because most of the royal factories were opened in other provinces.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Moreover, several conflicts between France and Britain during the 18th century resulted in British blockades which weakened the Breton economy, leading it to go into recession.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Two significant revolts occurred in the 17th and 18th centuries: the Revolt of the papier timbré (1675) and the Pontcallec conspiracy (1719).
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Both arose from attempts to resist centralisation and assert Breton constitutional exceptions to tax.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Many Bretons crossed the Atlantic to support the American War of Independence.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] These included naval officers such as Armand de Kersaint and soldiers such as Charles Armand Tuffin, marquis de la Rouërie.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The Duchy was legally abolished with the French Revolution that began in 1789 – and in 1790 the province of Brittany was divided into five departments: Côtes-du-Nord (later Côtes-d'Armor), Finistère, Ille-et-Vilaine, Loire-Inférieure (later Loire-Atlantique) and Morbihan.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Brittany essentially lost all its special privileges that existed under the Duchy.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Three years later, the area became a centre of royalist and Catholic resistance to the Revolution during the Chouannerie.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] During the 19th century, Brittany remained in economic recession, and many Bretons emigrated to other French regions, particularly to Paris.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] This trend remained strong until the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Nonetheless, the region was also modernising, with new roads and railways being built, and some places being industrialised.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Nantes specialised in shipbuilding and food processing (sugar, exotic fruits and vegetables, fish, etc.), Fougères in glass and shoe production, and metallurgy was practised in small towns such as Châteaubriant and Lochrist, known for its labour movements.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The region remained deeply Catholic, and during the Second Empire, the conservative values were strongly reasserted.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] When the Republic was re-established in 1871, there were rumours that Breton troops were mistrusted and mistreated at Camp Conlie during the Franco-Prussian War because of fears that they were a threat to the Republic.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] During the 19th century, the Breton language started to decline precipitously, mainly because of the Francization policy conducted under the Third Republic.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] On one hand, children were not allowed to speak Breton at school, and were punished by teachers if they did.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Famously, signs in schools read: "It is forbidden to speak Breton and to spit on the floor" ("*Il est interdit de parler Breton et de cracher par terre*").
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] At the same time, the Celtic Revival led to the foundation of the Breton Regionalist Union (URB) and later to independence movements linked to Irish, Welsh, and Scottish and Cornish independence parties in the UK, and to pan-Celticism.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] However, the audience of these movements remained very low and their ideas did not reach a large public until the 20th century.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The Seiz Breur movement, created in 1923, permitted a Breton artistic revival but its ties with Nazism and the collaborationism of the Breton National Party during World War II weakened Breton nationalism in the post-war period.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Brittany lost 240,000 men during the First World War.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The Second World War was also catastrophic for the region.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] It was invaded by Nazi Germany in 1940 and freed after Operation Cobra in August 1944.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] However, the areas around Saint-Nazaire and Lorient only surrendered on 10 and 11 May 1945, several days after the German capitulation.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The two port towns had been virtually destroyed by Allied air raids, like Brest and Saint-Malo, and other towns, such as Nantes and Rennes, had also suffered.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] In 1956, Brittany was legally reconstituted as the Region of Brittany, although the region excluded the ducal capital of Nantes and the surrounding area.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Nevertheless, Brittany retained its cultural distinctiveness, and a new cultural revival emerged during the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Bilingual schools were opened, singers started to write songs in Breton, and ecological catastrophes such as the Amoco Cadiz oil spill or the Erika oil spill and water pollution from intensive pig farming favoured new movements to protect the natural heritage.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Brittany as a political entity disappeared in 1790, when it was divided into five départements.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] These replaced the nine Catholic dioceses that appeared at the beginning of the Middle Ages.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] These were often called "pays" or "bro" ("country" in French and Breton) and they also served as fiscal and military districts.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Brittany is also divided between *Lower Brittany* ("Basse Bretagne" and "Breizh Izel"), corresponding to the western half, where Breton is traditionally spoken, and *Upper Brittany* ("Haute Bretagne" and "Breizh Uhel"), corresponding to the eastern half, where Gallo is traditionally spoken.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] During the French Revolution, four dioceses were suppressed and the five remaining ones were modified to have the same administrative borders as the départements.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Brittany has several historical capital cities.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] When it was an independent duchy, the Estates of Brittany, which can be compared to a parliament, met in various towns: Dinan, Ploërmel, Redon, Rennes, Vitré, Guérande, and, most of all, Vannes, where they met 19 times, and Nantes, 17 times.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The Court and the government were also very mobile, and each dynasty favoured its own castles and estates.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The dukes mostly lived in Nantes, Vannes, Redon, Rennes, Fougères, Dol-de-Bretagne, Dinan and Guérande.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] All these towns except Vannes and Guérande are located in Upper Brittany, thus not in the Breton speaking area.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Among all these towns, only Nantes, Rennes and Vannes, which were the biggest ones, could really pretend to the capital status.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The dukes were crowned in Rennes and they had a large castle there; it was however destroyed during the 15th century.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Vannes, on its side, was the seat of the Chamber of Accounts and of the Parliament until the union with France.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The Parliament was then transferred to Rennes, and the Chamber of Accounts to Nantes.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Nantes, nicknamed "the city of the Dukes of Brittany", was also the permanent residence of the last dukes.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The Château des ducs de Bretagne still stands in the city centre.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Nowadays, Rennes is the only official capital of the region of Brittany.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] It is also the seat of an ecclesiastical province encompassing Brittany and the Pays de la Loire region.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] During the French Revolution, Brittany was divided into five *départements*, each made up of three or four *arrondissements*.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The arrondissements are further divided in cantons, which are themselves made up of one or several communes.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The communes and the départements have a local council elected by their citizens, but arrondissements and cantons are not run by elected officials.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The cantons serve as an electoral district for the election of the département councils and arrondissements are run by a subprefect appointed by the French president.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The president also appoints a prefect in each département.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Because the départements are small and numerous, the French government tried to create wider regions during the 20th century.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] For the Breton nationalists, it was an occasion to recreate Brittany as a political and administrative entity, but the new region had to be economically efficient.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Nantes and its *département*, Loire-Atlantique, raised concerns because they were off-centered, more integrated with the Loire Valley than with the Breton peninsula.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The French government and local politicians also feared that Nantes, because of its population and its former Breton capital status, would have maintained a harmful competition with Rennes to get the regional institutions and investments.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Several drafts for French regions had been proposed since the 1920s, and the definitive regions were drawn in 1956.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The new Brittany had four départements, and Loire-Atlantique formed the Pays de la Loire region together with parts of Anjou, Maine and Poitou.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] In 1972, the regions received their present competencies, with an elected regional council.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Since then, the region of Brittany has had its own council and administrative bodies.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] When the region of Brittany was created, several local politicians opposed the exclusion of Loire-Atlantique, and the question still remains.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The obstacles to reunification are the same as in 1956: having Nantes in Brittany could harm the position of Rennes and create an economic imbalance between Lower and Upper Brittany.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Moreover, the Pays de la Loire region could not exist without Loire-Atlantique, because it would lose its political and economic capital.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Without Loire-Atlantique, the other départements would not form an efficient region any more, and would have to integrate neighbouring regions such as the Centre-Val de Loire and Nouvelle-Aquitaine.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] However, several institutions have backed the reunification, such as the regional council of Brittany since 2008 and the Loire-Atlantique council since 2001.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Some politicians like Jean-Marc Ayrault, the former French prime minister and former mayor of Nantes, favour instead the creation of a "Greater West region", which would encompass Brittany and the Pays de la Loire region.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Polls show that 58% of the Bretons and 62% of the inhabitants in Loire-Atlantique favour the reunification.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Until the end of the 20th century, Brittany had been characterised by a strong Catholic and conservative influence.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] However, some areas such as the industrial region around Saint-Nazaire and Lorient and the surroundings of Tréguier are traditional Socialist and Communist strongholds.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Left-wing parties, mainly the Socialist party and the Greens, have become more powerful after the 1970s and they have formed a majority in the Regional Council of Brittany since 2004.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The Loire-Atlantique and Ille-et-Vilaine councils have also been held by the left since 2004.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The Socialist party has held the Côtes-d'Armor council since 1976, and the Finistère council since 1998.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] On its side, Morbihan remains a right-wing stronghold.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The local parties have a very small audience, except the Union Démocratique Bretonne which has seats at the Regional Council and in other local assemblies.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] It advocates more autonomy for the region and its positions are very close to the Socialist parties.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] It also has a strong ecological orientation.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The audience of far-right parties is lower in Brittany than in the rest of France.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Brittany is the largest French peninsula.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] It is around 34,030 km2 (13,140 sq mi) and stretches toward the northwest and the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] It is bordered to the north by the English Channel, to the south by the Bay of Biscay and the waters located between the western coast and Ushant Island form the Iroise Sea.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The Breton coast is very indented, with many cliffs, rias and capes.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The Gulf of Morbihan is a vast natural harbour with some forty islands that is almost a closed sea.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] In total, around 800 islands lie off the mainland; the largest being Belle Île, in the south.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Brittany has over 2,860 km (1,780 mi) of coastline; it represents a third of the total French coastline.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The region is generally hilly because it corresponds to the western end of the Armorican Massif, a very old range that also extends in Normandy and the Pays de la Loire region.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Because of this continuity, the Breton border with the rest of France is not marked by any strong geographical landmark, apart from the river Couesnon, which separates Brittany from Normandy.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The Armorican Massif reaches its maximum elevation outside of Brittany, in neighbouring Mayenne, at 417 m, and slopes towards the west before straightening on its western extremity, with the Montagnes Noires and the Monts d'Arrée.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The highest hill in Brittany is the *Roc'h Ruz* in the Monts d'Arrée, at 385 m (1,263 ft).
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] It is closely followed by several neighbouring hills culminating at around 384 m above sea level.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Coastal areas are usually named *Armor* or *Arvor* ("by the sea" in Breton), and the inland is called *Argoat* ("by the forest").
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The best soils were primitively covered by large forests which had been progressively replaced by bocage during the Middle Ages.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The Breton bocage, with its small fields enclosed by thick hedgerows, has almost disappeared since the 1960s to fit the modern agricultural needs and methods, particularly mechanisation.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Several forests still exist, such as the Paimpont forest, sometimes said to be the Arthurian Brocéliande.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The poor and rocky areas are covered by large heathland and moorlands, and Brittany has several marshes, like the Brière, included in a regional natural park.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Another regional park encompasses the Monts d'Arrée and the Iroise seacoast.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The Iroise Sea is also a UNESCO biosphere reserve.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The Breton peninsula appeared during the Cadomian Orogeny, which formed its northern coastline, between Guingamp and Fougères.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The southern part emerged during the Hercynian orogeny.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] At the same time, an intense volcanic activity left large quantities of granite.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Between the Cadomian and Hercynian periods, the region was submerged several times and the sea left fossils and sedimentary rocks, mostly schist and sandstone.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Because of the absence of limestone, soils in Brittany are usually acidic.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The Armorican massif straightened and flattened several times during the formation of the Pyrenees and the Alps.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Changes in sea levels and climate led to a strong erosion and to the formation of more sedimentary rocks.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Metamorphism is responsible for the distinctive local blue schist and for the rich subsoil of the Groix island, which comprises glaucophane and epidote.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] During the Quaternary glaciations, Brittany was covered by loess and rivers started to fill the valleys with alluvial deposits.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The valleys themselves were a result of a strong tectonic activity between the African and the Eurasian Plate.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The present Breton landscape did not acquire its final shape before one million years ago.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The Breton subsoil is characterised by a huge amount of fractures that form a large aquifer containing several millions square meters of water.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Brittany lies within the north temperate zone.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] It has a changeable, maritime climate, similar to Cornwall.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Rainfall occurs regularly but sunny, cloudless days are also common.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] In the summer months, temperatures in the region can reach 30 °C (86 °F), yet the climate remains comfortable, especially when compared to the French regions located south of the Loire.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The temperature difference between summer and winter is about 15 degrees, but it varies depending on the proximity of the sea.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The weather is generally milder on the seacoast than inland but rainfall occurs with the same intensity on both.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The Monts d'Arrée, despite their low elevation, have much more rainfall than the rest of the region.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] The south coast, between Lorient and Pornic, enjoys more than 2,000 hours of sunshine per year.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] Brittany's wildlife is typical of France with several distinctions.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] On one hand, the region, due to its long coastline, has a rich oceanic fauna, and some birds cannot be seen in other French regions.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] On the other hand, the species found in the inland are usually common for France, and because Brittany is a peninsula, the number of species is lower in its western extremity than in the eastern part.
[src:brittany/brittany-p01] A variety of seabirds can be seen close to the seaside, which is home to colonies of cormorants, gulls, razorbills, northern gannets, common murres and Atlantic puffins.
